<HEADLINE>
FT  11 DEC 92 / UK Company News: Polly creditors lose last tranche of frozen
funds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE FINAL tranche of funds frozen in English accounts of the Central Bank of
Northern Cyprus at the request of administrators of Polly Peck International
has been recovered by the bank, its solicitors said yesterday.
The move means creditors of the collapsed electronics, fruit and leisure
company have lost all security over the funds.
Mr David Janney of Theodore Goddard, the solicitors acting for the bank,
said yesterday that the remaining Pounds 4.7m had been called down by the
Central Bank in the ordinary course of its business.
The PPI administrators had originally succeeded in obtaining a court
injunction freezing the British accounts of the Central Bank. However, in
subsequent litigation the so-called Mareva injunctions, named after the
first case in which one was imposed, were relaxed and subsequently
discharged.
</TEXT>
