</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAGGIE URRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PILKINGTON'S share price rose yesterday, but the directors were given a
rough ride when presenting the interim results to analysts.
They questioned the maintenance of the dividend at 2.93p, given that it was
paid entirely from reserves.
There was little good news in the figures, which showed a 70 per cent drop
in pre-tax profits from Pounds 50.6m to Pounds 15.1m in the six months to
September 30.
This was is in spite of Pilkington taking an annual Pounds 150m of costs out
of the business over the past three years, with a further Pounds 24m going
in the first half.
Group turnover of Pounds 1.2bn was slightly up when sales of discontinued
operations were excluded.
But operating profits of Pounds 46.7m compared with Pounds 89m, including
Pounds 19.4m from discontinued operations, mainly the South African
business.
Investment income and associates contributed Pounds 8.4m, down from Pounds
14.2m.
That left the interest charge of Pounds 37.4m (Pounds 48.6m), covered only
1.5 times. Exceptional items were Pounds 2.6m, against Pounds 4m, although
they are likely to reach Pounds 10m for the full year.
The group's tax charge of Pounds 14.7m (Pounds 30.4m) was high because
losses in the UK - of Pounds 8.3m at the operating level - could not be
offset against tax paid on overseas profits of Pounds 56m. Advance
corporation tax on the dividend could not be offset either.
After minorities took Pounds 6.7m (Pounds 12.4m) there was a loss for
shareholders of Pounds 6.3m (profit Pounds 7.8m) or 0.8p a share (earnings
of 1p).
The shares added 3p to 87p.
Mr Roger Leverton, who became chief executive in July, said capacity
utilisation was about 85 per cent. Variable costs of production were low.
About 10 per cent of sales were of new, higher technology products
introduced in the past five years, which earned much higher margins than
standard products. Mr Leverton said he aimed to increase their contribution
to 15 per cent of sales.
Another aim was to continue to cut costs. Capital spending had totalled
Pounds 1bn over the past three years, but this would be cut, working capital
would be squeezed further and debt brought down.
Operating profits from flat and safety glass fell to Pounds 38.3m (Pounds
52.3m). The decline in European profits from Pounds 32.7m to Pounds 17.2m
and North American to Pounds 2m (Pounds 6.5m), was offset partly by a Pounds
6m rise from other areas to Pounds 19.1m. Visioncare, which includes Sola
and the US contact lens business, had flat profits of Pounds 11.6m.
</TEXT>
