FT  11 DEC 92 / Clinton names five who will shape US economy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
US PRESIDENT-ELECT Bill Clinton yesterday reached into Congress and Wall
Street for five senior positions on the team that will shape his
administration's economic policies.
In unveiling his nominees, whom he described as 'seasoned, skilled and
incredibly able', Mr Clinton repeatedly emphasised that sustainable economic
growth was contingent on 'a serious, credible, long-term deficit reduction
policy'.
As expected, Mr Lloyd Bentsen, the 71-year-old senator from Texas and
chairman of the Senate finance committee, becomes Treasury secretary, with
Mr Roger Altman, 46, of the Blackstone Group, Wall Street investment banker,
as his deputy.
Congressman Leon Panetta from California, 54, and chairman of the House
budget committee, will take over as director of the Office of Management and
Budget. Dr Alice Rivlin, 61, who is attached to the Brookings Institution,
will be Mr Panetta's deputy.
Mr Robert Rubin, also 54, and co-chairman of Goldman Sachs Wall Street
investment bank, takes the new position of economic counsellor to the
president, operating from the White House.
Mr Clinton did not yesterday name a new head of the Council of Economic
Advisers, as some had expected, but said this did not mean he intended to
downgrade the CEA, which he said would continue to provide independent
economic consultation and advice.
Mr Rubin's job, he added, was to be co-ordinator of a new economic advisory
body under the president's chairmanship and analogous to the existing
National Security Council. Its members would include those named yesterday
and other hitherto unrepresented cabinet departments, such as commerce,
labour and the interior.
Mr Bentsen, Mr Panetta and Dr Rivlin bring formidable qualifications and
congressional experience in budgetary matters to the new administration, an
indication of Mr Clinton's determination to tackle the deficit of more than
Dollars 300bn (Pounds 197bn) while pursuing the goals of 'a high wage, high
growth, strong and vital economy'.
Mr Panetta, for example, is known as a deficit-reduction 'hawk'. Dr Rivlin,
the only economist of the five, set up the independent Congressional Budget
Office in 1975.
Talented line-up, Page 8
Observer, Page 21
