<HEADLINE>
FT  11 DEC 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Television, we are told, is an ephemeral thing. My predecessor on the FT
even called his book of collected television criticism 'The Ephemeral Art'.
Yet at 7.30 tonight you can see the latest episode of Coronation Street, the
series which gets the biggest single audience in Britain, currently more
than 19m, and which started 32 years ago this week. How un-ephemeral can you
get? At 7.40 comes another edition of What The Papers Say, running since
1956. Later you will find the British movie Children Of The Damned enjoying
its umpteenth screening. An SF frightener adapted from John Wyndham's book,
it was made 28 years ago (12.10 C4). It is followed by an episode from The
Twilight Zone which was made in the US between 1959 and 1964. Also this
evening you can watch such long established television personalities as
David Frost in the embarrassing 'game' Through The Keyhole, John Cleese
presenting Prisoners Of Conscience, Esther Rantzen with the syrupy Hearts Of
Gold, and Terry Wogan with his Friday Night. If this lot are ephemeral,
heaven preserve us from the implacably entrenched.
</TEXT>
