<HEADLINE>
FT  11 DEC 92 / Street discovery fetches Pounds 935,000: Saleroom
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE HIGHLIGHT of a Bonhams sale of Old Masters yesterday was a painting
bought in a street market 30 years ago for a few shillings.
The still life of sea bream, oranges, garlic, a cloth and kitchen utensils,
by Luis Melendez, sold for Pounds 935,000, a record for the 18th-century
Spanish artist.
The sale brought in Pounds 1.45m, a record for any sale at the Knightsbridge
auction house.
At Sotheby's yesterday an aquamanile (a bronze medieval container for
washing the hands) in the shape of a knight on horseback sold for Pounds
660,000. The price was an auction record for an aquamanile. The aquamanile,
made in north Germany in about 1200, was bought by a Continental collector.
The top estimate was Pounds 80,000.
The Bowleaze jewel, a rare 9th-century Anglo-Saxon jewel, probably the
terminal of a manuscript pointer, also received considerable pre-sale
interest and was bought by Mr Robin Symes, a London dealer, for Pounds
41,800. The jewel was found in 1990 on the beach at Bowleaze Cove in Dorset.
It had apparently fallen from the cliff in a landslide.
The European works of art auction totalled Pounds 1.48m in the morning
session and was 12.8 per cent unsold. Mr Danny Katz, another London dealer,
paid Pounds 93,500 for a Florentine bronze stallion made in the workshops of
Antonio Susini in about 1600.
At Bonhams on Wednesday, Ikemasa, a Japanese dealer, paid Pounds 682,000 for
a blue and white early Ming brush washer. The dish re-emerged after being
stolen in 1984 and was sold by Lloyd's of London.
</TEXT>
