<HEADLINE>
FT  11 DEC 92 / Shephard to scrap funding for union ballots
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT yesterday removed a further plank of state support from trade
unionism and collective bargaining by announcing the phased withdrawal of
financial aid for secret ballots and trade union training.
The sums of money are not large - unions received Pounds 4m last year for
ballots and Pounds 2m for training - but the announcement is a further blow
to union hopes of opening a dialogue with the government and re-establishing
some national influence.
Yesterday Mrs Gillian Shephard, the employment secretary, justified the
withdrawal of public subsidy for ballots by saying: 'Fewer than 50 per cent
of employees have their pay determined, directly or indirectly, by
negotiations between employers and trade unions.'
The government will meet 75 per cent of the cost of ballots in 1993-94, 50
per cent in 1994-95, 25 per cent in 1995-96. There will then be no further
payments.
Funding for secret ballots, introduced in 1980, was initially rejected by
the Trades Union Congress, but last night Mr Norman Willis, TUC general
secretary, described the move as 'a vicious and calculated blow to destroy
state support for good union practice'.
Mrs Shephard has spoken of the 'war' with the unions being at an end, but
the government has continued taking the axe to union-supported institutions
such as the National Economic Development Council.
The employment bill, currently at committee stage in the Commons and likely
to become law early next year, continues that policy. The bill proposes to
abolish Wages Councils, which set minimum wages for 2.5m workers, and to
abolish the duty of Acas, the government conciliation service, to encourage
the extension of collective bargaining.
Yesterday the clause in the bill that requires employees to agree every
three years to the automatic deduction of union subscriptions from their pay
packets was passed by 13 votes to 12. The unions fear that reform to
'check-off' might cause the loss of as many as 20 per cent of members and
lead to further financial pressure on unions.
</TEXT>
