<HEADLINE>
FT  11 DEC 92 / Consumer retail spending stays steady
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RETAIL spending during the run-up to Christmas is showing more stability
than last year, according to Transax, the Birmingham-based cheque guarantee
organisation.
Last Saturday, retailers requested Transax to guarantee more than 27,400
personal cheques - 0.5 per cent more than the previous Saturday. In the
corresponding two Saturdays last year, there was a decline of 6.6 per cent
in the number of cheque guarantee requests, with trading picking up only in
the last weekend before Christmas, Transax reported.
The fact that cheque payments in shops have not fallen away this year offers
a further indication that consumer confidence may be slowly reviving. It
follows official figures this week showing a slight increase in the amount
of net consumer debt during October.
Transax provides a cheque guarantee service to about 23,000 shops and
stores.
Retailers, offered a cheque by a customer for a sum greater than that
specified on the cheque card, seek authorisation to accept it from Transax.
Once Transax gives that authorisation, it guarantees full payment to the
retailer even if the cheque bounces.
The volume of calls from retailers over the last two Saturdays suggested
that, in comparison with last year, trade has been higher in jewellery
stores, off-linences and wine merchants.
</TEXT>
