<HEADLINE>
FT  11 DEC 92 / Parliament and Politics: Lamont firm on his place at
Treasury
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Norman Lamont sought yesterday to quash suggestions that Mr John Major
might decide to move him from the Treasury in a new year reshuffle. The
chancellor insisted that he would be delivering the next Budget in March.
But the prime minister pointedly declined to rule out entirely the
possibility of changes at the top of his government. While senior aides said
that he had given 'no thought' to the issue, Mr Major would say only that he
refused to be drawn into a reshuffle speculation.
In a series of television interviews on the eve of the European Community
summit in Edinburgh, the prime minister said: 'I will deal with reshuffles
as and when we come to them.'
Aides believe that Mr Major is unlikely to move Mr Lamont before the Budget,
in spite of a growing view among cabinet colleagues that the chancellor no
longer commands the confidence of most Conservative MPs. By refusing to rule
out explicitly such a change, the prime minister is keeping his options
open.
Mr Lamont's comments were seen by Conservative colleagues as a veiled threat
to Mr Major that he is ready to quit the government rather than accept
another cabinet post if the prime minister seeks to move him. Mr Lamont -
one of the handful of Euro-sceptics in the cabinet - has the support of many
of the rightwing MPs on whom Mr Major must depend to secure ratification of
the Maastricht treaty.
Pressed during a television interview about persistent rumours of a new year
reshuffle, Mr Lamont responded: 'I am here as chancellor and I will be
delivering the Budget.'
He acknowledged that such a decision was a 'matter for the prime minister',
but then repeated that he would not be moved before March.
Cabinet colleagues judge that Mr Kenneth Clarke is the strongest candidate
to replace Mr Lamont at the Treasury. But the home secretary's strongly
pro-European views would enrage the Euro-sceptics, suggesting that his
chances for the job would be improved if a reshuffle is delayed until after
the Commons completes ratification of Maastricht in the summer.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
