<PROFILE>_AN-CLKB5ACBFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921211
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 DEC 92 / Parliament and Politics: Tories to revamp strategy for
by-election campaigns
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Conservative party is preparing to sharpen its by-election campaigning
as part of the shake-up in the party organisation begun by Sir Norman
Fowler, the party chairman.
One key element in the changes will be a move to send a senior party figure
to a constituency immediately the need for a by-election arises, to advise
local party officers about the intense media pressure of the campaign so
they can take account of that in choosing a candidate.
Contacts between the local campaign and party headquarters at Smith Square
in London will also be improved. The most likely course is that a national
party officer or experienced MP will be seconded to the campaign, in
addition to the 'minder' that every by-election candidate has under present
arrangements.
Concern over the party's dismal performance in by-elections during the last
parliament has intensified because of the government's overall Commons
majority of just 21. In the last parliament, the government held just three
of the 10 seats it sought to defend, although it won them all back at the
April general election.
The changes in the party organisation are expected to include a swathe of
job losses as the party makes progress in reducing its Pounds 15m deficit.
While final decisions are not expected until the new year, the party's area
offices, which at present employ about 60 staff, are likely to bear the
brunt.
Streamlining the 12 area offices might mean that some are amalgamated,
although party figures emphasise that they think areas with distinct
identities, such as Wales and the south-west, should still be able to mount
their own operations.
The Scottish organisation is thus unlikely to be seriously affected.
In an effort to improve the effectiveness of local campaigning, party
officials are also considering 'twinning' safe Tory seats with marginals
where the constituencies are next to each other.
The party is already planning a more co-ordinated effort in the elections to
the European parliament. In particular, senior officers are already clear
that Mr John Major must play a more active part than Baroness Thatcher did
in the campaign for the 1989 Euro-elections.
</TEXT>
