<HEADLINE>
FT  11 DEC 92 / Parliament and Politics: Labour urges City regulation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE IS a 'very real trade-off' between the cost of financial services
regulation and the cost of compensation, Mr Anthony Nelson, economic
secretary to the Treasury, told MPs last night as he fended off Labour
charges of 'giving up on the fight to put City regulation in order'.
Many would be content to pay more for regulation if they thought that was
likely to have an impact on compensation costs, he suggested. Even the best
system of supervision would be wasted without the right people and the
willingness to exercise it.
As the Commons approved regulations to implement the second European banking
directive, he reiterated his comments to the Financial Times last week that
there was much that could be done to beef up financial services supervision
without resorting to new legislation.
'The City wanted self-regulation, it has got a high degree of
self-regulation, it must now self-regulate,' he said.
He was responding to a call from Mr Alistair Darling, shadow Treasury
spokesman, to 'set up a regulatory system with teeth' that would be good for
the consumer, efficient for industry and vital for the good name of the
City.
Prompted by Mr Darling, Mr Nelson admitted that the government would have
liked the recently agreed European investment services directive to have
come into force at the same time as the banking directive in January -
rather than in 1996, as currently planned.
He described the scheduled timetable for implementation as 'realistic'.
Addressing last night's directive, which provides the legal framework for a
single market in banking, Mr Nelson said the BCCI affair had demonstrated
the difficulties faced by supervisors in dealing with complex international
conglomerates.
But he argued that the measure's underlying supervisory principles remained
'valid in a post-BCCI world'. Those principles 'in many respects' were part
of the process of ensuring that a bank could not in future develop as BCCI
did.
That view was 'echoed' in the conclusions of the recent Bingham report.
</TEXT>
