<HEADLINE>
FT  11 DEC 92 / Nissan UK reaches pay and employment deal with Sunderland
and Cranfield staff
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
NISSAN UK, the Japanese car company, has reached a two-year pay and
employment deal with the 5,000 staff at its north-east England plant at
Sunderland and its engineering centre at Cranfield, Bedfordshire.
The deal is the first significant private-sector pay rise agreed since the
government announced a 1.5 per cent pay ceiling for the public sector. The
award, effective from January, will raise salaries by 4 per cent in the
first year and 3.5 per cent in the second.
If UK inflation rises above 4.5 per cent in 1994 salaries will rise on a
point-for-point basis thereafter. That means that if UK inflation rises to
5.5 per cent in 1994, then salaries will rise an extra 1 percentage point to
4.5 per cent. In the previous two years the award was 10.5 per cent falling
to 7 per cent in the second year.
The deal compares with a two-year deal at Jaguar that gave workers 4 per
cent in both years with an inflation trigger in the second.
Employees at Rover had an 18-month deal worth a minimum of 7.3 per cent.
Ford is in the second year of a two-year deal. Peugeot Talbot has still to
settle.
The deal at Nissan UK will give manufacturing staff a basic wage of Pounds
15,382.
</TEXT>
