<HEADLINE>
FT  11 DEC 92 / Bombs injure 10 people at N London shopping centre
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TEN PEOPLE were injured yesterday by two bombs that exploded in a north
London shopping centre.
The small devices went off at Wood Green Shopping City at 9.30am and 9.35am
as police and shop staff were evacuating the area. They were planted in
rubbish bins, 50 yards apart, outside branches of Argos and WH Smith.
Commander David Tucker, head of Scotland Yard's anti-terrorist branch, said:
'I have no doubt this is the latest in the mainland campaign by the IRA.'
The attack followed an explosion on Wednesday night in a car parked near the
Woodside Park Underground station, also in north London. No one was injured.
Mr John Major, the prime minister, commenting yesterday on the explosions,
said: 'It is vitally important that people remain vigilant in the period up
to Christmas.'
Mr Major, who was speaking in Edinburgh on his arrival for the EC summit,
said a great deal had been done to improve security across the UK.
The Wood Green blasts, which caused limited damage to shops, were preceded
by warning calls that the police described as a deliberately misleading trap
for officers clearing the area. Scotland Yard said that three warning calls
were made at 9.15am, 9.16am and 9.18am. The first call, using an IRA code
word, was made to a news agency and said the bomb would explode in 20
minutes.
The injured, four police officers and six members of the public, were taken
to North Middlesex Hospital suffering from shock and cuts.
The Association of London Authorities last night called on the home
secretary to meet the costs of the Metropolitan Police's counter-terrorism
operations.
Mr Derek Sawyer, association policing spokesman, said London taxpayers
should not have to meet the full cost of tackling the IRA's latest campaign.
Mr Sawyer said: 'It is important that the Home Office recognises the amount
of extra police time and resources which the spate of terrorist incidents
requires and provides the Met with extra money to cope with these extra
responsibilities.'
He said a meeting with police had disclosed that the police overtime budget
was expected to rise by more than 7 per cent next year, after having fallen
for several years.
</TEXT>
