<HEADLINE>
FT  11 DEC 92 / Accountancy firms fall short of standards
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MANY ACCOUNTANCY firms are failing to comply with the audit requirements
introduced last year, the first annual report of their self-regulatory body
shows.
Only 11 of the 158 audit firms so far randomly inspected passed all 13 tests
devised by the Department of Trade and Industry and the Joint Monitoring
Unit, the regulatory body jointly owned by the three UK chartered
accountancy bodies.
The findings come in a confidential internal report due to be sent today to
Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, for consideration by
officials before publication next week.
The report emphasises that most of the 10,200 registered firms have taken
steps to comply with the audit regime introduced in October 1991, and that
it is too soon to make a definitive statement on the quality of work carried
out.
The Joint Monitoring Unit unearthed widespread failures in the systems and
procedures that the regulations require. Its findings will fuel criticism of
the present quality of auditing.
The unit visited 291 firms in the 12 months to September - meeting its
targets - of which 143 were to prepare for registration, to offer training
or in response to requests.
Of the remainder, which were randomly selected during April to September, 67
firms were not conducting 'cold' or continuous reviews of their audit work
as required by the regulations.
The audit procedures of 39 were not subject to quality control procedures
and 41 had not planned their audits. The unit emphasised that the findings
might indicate inadequate documentation at least as much as unsatisfactory
audits.
It also judged 10 firms not to be independent from their audit clients, and
identified nine that were not competent. The professional accountancy bodies
have refused to register at least 12 firms or practitioners as auditors, and
have so far withdrawn registration from 10. They received more than 183
complaints during the year.
The report concludes: 'The weaknesses thus far identified do not appear to
indicate any general shortfall in the quality of audit work but do
demonstrate in many cases procedural shortfalls.'
It recommends making audit regulation more economical and more rapid in the
future, and says that more meaningful ways of analysing data from monitoring
visits to firms need to be developed.
It says many firms believe that audit regulation was introduced in response
to a few prominent company collapses, and are concerned at the high cost of
the new regime.
Audit registration fees received from firms are expected to be about Pounds
4m this year, against expenditure on regulation and the Auditing Practices
Board of Pounds 3.6m this year and Pounds 3.5m in the previous three years.
</TEXT>
