FT  11 DEC 92 / Rioting spreads to Yemeni capital
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SANAA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
RIOTS engulfed five Yemeni towns, including the capital Sanaa, yesterday and
the government said 11 people were killed and 48 civilians and policemen
were injured, Reuter reports from Sanaa.
In Sanaa, where there were no reports of casualties, police fired shots in
the air and tear gas to stop hundreds of demonstrators reaching the
presidential palace.
Witnesses said crowds set fire to government cars. Dozens of people were
arrested and some were beaten by police before being put on trucks and taken
away, the witnesses said.
The disorders were the worst to rock Yemen since the north and south merged
in 1990. Strikes and demonstrations to demand more pay and a price freeze on
essential foodstuffs have dogged Yemen since unification.
The government, under its policy of democratic reforms, has tolerated them
in the past.
