<HEADLINE>
FT  11 DEC 92 / World Trade News: Consumer protest at world trade plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THREE HUNDRED consumer, citizen and environmental groups from around the
world yesterday demanded that Uruguay Round negotiators abandon the idea of
creating a Multilateral Trading Organisation with 'massive powers' to
override multilateral, regional and national rules.
Congress Watch, a national consumer group in Washington, published a
statement signed by groups in 70 countries. It said the MTO, proposed as
part of the Uruguay Round, would impose policies on weaker countries; damage
environmental, safety and consumer interests; and reduce international
controls over monopolies.
A senior US trade official yesterday said the Bush administration also had
'a number of concerns' about the proposed text creating an MTO. It would
only support an MTO if its underlying rules were 'reasonable and fair' and
if it did not result 'in a kind of usurpation of functions of sovereign
governments'.
However, the US is not yet satisfied with the underlying rules on
investment, dumping and subsidies. The official suggested that it would be
possible to complete the round without an MTO but with a strengthened
dispute settlement system.
The American delegation in Geneva seems to be struggling with the lame duck
status of the Bush administration, although it stresses the continuity of US
trade policy.
Meanwhile, the US industry groups seeking to reduce tariffs to zero on such
products as paper, wood products, and copper are also worried about lack of
progress. Their support for a final Gatt package is considered crucial for
congressional passage.
Intel Corporation has dropped out of the 'Zero Tariff Coalition' to urge a
break in the Gatt talks until after President-elect Bill Clinton is
inaugurated.
</TEXT>
