<HEADLINE>
FT  11 DEC 92 / The Edinburgh Summit: Spain set to reject budget compromise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   EDINBURGH
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SPAIN is likely to reject British proposals to break the deadlock over the
Delors II plan for future financing of the Community.
The British presidency's compromise keeps the same ceiling on revenue of
1.25 per cent of EC gross national product, but allocates marginal increases
in transfers to poorer member states.
It also adds small amounts to spending on policies like research and
development and foreign policy, which France in particular is keen to see.
Mr Jacques Delors, Commission president, had originally proposed a one-third
increase in the EC budget, raising the revenue base from its ceiling of 1.2
per cent to 1.37 per cent by 1997. This would have meant an increase in the
annual Community budget from Ecu66.8bn (Pounds 54bn) now to Ecu87.5bn in
1997, in today's money.
Mr Delors subsequently suggested raising the revenue ceiling to 1.32 per
cent of GNP by 1999, increasing the budget to Ecu86.2bn (in 1992 money) by
then, and giving the poorer countries close to the doubling in development
aid the Commission originally planned.
Spain - in alliance with Ireland, Portugal, Greece and the Commission - had
said the UK's suggested ceiling was unacceptable. Last night Spanish
officials said formally they were still studying the new proposals, but
privately they dismissed them as a non-starter.
The main changes in the UK proposal are to add an extra Ecu1.25bn to the
cohesion fund over 1993 to 1999, raising it to Ecu13.5bn, and to increase
slightly structural funds for backward regions.
The cohesion fund, created at Maastricht on Spanish insistence, is to help
Spain, Ireland, Portugal and Greece to meet EC environmental standards and
build up transport links with the rest of Europe. The structural funds,
however, apportion much more to the EC's backward regions, located largely
in these countries. It is these funds which will be the main battlefield in
today's negotiations.
The European Commission, supported by such countries as France, Belgium and
Luxembourg, has said it fears today's debate could polarise between the rich
north and poorer south.
</TEXT>
