<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / EC seeks closer policy ties with eastern Europe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE European Commission is proposing to involve the EC's central European
allies in common European foreign policy-making.
It also wants to hold enlarged meetings of the EC Council of Ministers with
them on trans-European collaboration in energy, environment, transport and
telecommunications policy. The proposal, in a confidential Commission report
discussed by EC foreign ministers over lunch on Tuesday, will be put to the
12 heads of government at tomorrow's Edinburgh summit.
It goes further than before in trying to draw the Community's eastern
neighbours into European integration, and is clearly intended to signal that
the EC remains outward-looking despite the crisis over the Maastricht
treaty.
The root idea in the new Commission paper on eastern Europe retrieves EC
external affairs commissioner Frans Andriessen's 1991 proposal on associate
membership of the Community for east and central European states intending
to join the EC. The idea is to offer these countries a stake in the European
union foreseen by Maastricht, in advance of full membership.
The front-running EC candidates in central Europe - the Czechs, Hungarians
and Poles - are thought to need a decade more to restructure their economies
before they could assume the competition obligations of the EC's single
market.
In the meantime, the Commission paper argues that the EC must speed up their
access to its market for goods such as food, steel and textiles, in which
eastern Europe has a comparative advantage.
The Commission says the EC should formally accept the east Europeans as
applicants, arguing that this would stimulate economic reform and
investment, and 'discourage excessive nationalism'. The so-called 'Europe
accords' the EC has with Hungary, Poland and Czechoslovakia, and which it is
exploring with Bulgaria, Romania and Albania, only state that these
countries see moves towards a free trade zone with the EC as a stepping
stone to membership.
The Commission advocates that the first three countries should be involved
in working groups and as observers at certain meetings of the 12 on foreign
policy. It suggests that this relationship could deepen as the EC develops a
fully-fledged common foreign and security policy as prescribed by
Maastricht.
The second main proposal is to let east European ministers sit in EC
councils discussing environment, transport and infrastructure policy of
common interest - though it hedges on whether they would be allowed to vote.
Mr Andriessen said on Tuesday these ideas were 'very well-received' by EC
foreign ministers.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
International Page 4
</PAGE>
