<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / Survey of Software at Work - Winter 1992 (23): Risks are
quickly assessed - Mortgage applications
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID TEBBUTT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE PROCESS of getting a mortgage was at one time helped enormously by the
rapport the borrower established with the lender. This would dictate how
much effort went into following up references and credit enquiries.
Nowadays, in the computer, the lender has a powerful ally in the battle
against fraudulent applications, taking over much of the work that used to
require human involvement. It can trigger automatic searches of remote
databases over the telephone lines without user intervention. Underwriters
can now assess risk, knowing that the computer has armed them with every
piece of information which they need.
One company which makes very sophisticated use of computing and
communications technology is the Household Mortgage Corporation. Using the
entries in the mortgage application form, its Assist Computer system can
immediately trigger enquiries into the personal circumstances of the
applicant.
By connecting to the Infolink Consumer Database, it can find out whether the
employer is doing well, whether the individual has a history of bad debt, or
whether they have a county court judgment against them.
HMC's own Unisys computer system holds information about how successful
loans have been to different types of borrower in the past. The company
plans to re-assess this information periodically, to ensure that emerging
behaviour patterns are being trapped. This knowledge is matched against the
searched information, the personal details (age, sex, present accommodation)
of the applicant and details of the loan, in order to assess the risk. When
all the information has been gathered and weighed by the computer, its
conclusions and supporting information are presented to the underwriter for
further interpretation.
Richard Anderson, head of underwriting at HMC, started thinking about the
possibilities of a new computer system in 1989 - 'we had a high standard of
underwriting, and we wanted to maintain this when the volume of business
rose again,' he says.
'Our industry has a history of great peaks and great troughs, but we cannot
staff for the peaks. We have to be consistently prudent, whatever the
business pattern. We want to check every mortgage application without
increasing the number of staff. Therefore, mechanical assistance was
needed.'
IN his search for a computer system which would meet the unusual needs of
his organisation, he found many packages which did part of the job but
nothing which matched exactly. In the end, he chose Infolink Decision
Services because it was prepared to build something specially for the
company. Infolink had built intelligent systems for other companies so it
understood HMC's requirements.
The on-line costs are minimal, compared with the amounts of money involved
in a loan, and although the company makes heavy use of Infolink, it still
pays on a search by search basis, the cost per search falling as the volume
rises.
The system has brought all the benefits expected, including an ability to
turn a loan application round in 24 hours. Mr Anderson considers all new
sources of electronic data as they become available.
For example, a historical voter's roll has now been developed, so it is easy
to check on how long applicants have lived at their current address. Land
registry records will prove invaluable once they become computerised. He
advises potential users of similar systems to be absolutely clear about what
they want to achieve before approaching the application developers and data
providers.
'There are no magic answers,' he says. With this kind of sophisticated
system, no-one is going to deliver it off-the-shelf.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XIX
</PAGE>
</DOC>
