<DOCNO>FT924-2778</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CLKB5AH6FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921210
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / Survey of Software at Work - Winter 1992 (22): No longer
smothered by paper documents - Stockbroking applications / David Tebbutt
tells how stockbrokers Hoare Govett are moving away from data on paper
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID TEBBUTT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FORWARD-LOOKING companies have dispensed with their dusty libraries, and
even dustier librarians. In their place they have high-tech information
centres and information services managers.
The library function is, of course, still there. It has simply been enhanced
and improved by the addition of electronic, and therefore easily accessed,
information.
Hoare Govett, the stockbroker, was drowning in paper documents on the
business activities of thousands of companies. This had a number of
disadvantages. First of all, finding the exact record of interest was only
possible if its identity was already known. Searches could only be made by
company name, not by its attributes.
Other problems with paper-based systems include mis-filing. A mis-filed
record was lost for ever. Theft is perhaps too strong a word, but brokers
and analysts would often borrow paper records which would never be seen
again. And, of course, the costs of paper-based systems were high because of
the storage space and filing staff needed.
Hoare Govett's first move away from paper came when it started using
microfiche pictures of original documents. This was more a mechanical
process, but it did give a glimpse of the improved security, staffing and
space savings which were to come with the advent of CD-ROM and on-line
databases.
The company's first on-line systems were Datastream and Textline. Datastream
is a statistical database, covering companies, commodities, government and
economic statistics, while Textline contains synopses and full articles from
the world's press.
When the present information services manager, Janet Inglis, joined the
company in 1986, both systems were already running on dedicated terminals.
Later that year, Hoare Govett signed for its first on-line service, the
McCarthy press cutting service.
Previously McCarthy had provided press cuttings reproduced in card index
format. The Hoare Govett staff were quite resistant to the idea of
electronic information. They felt more secure with the familiar paper
documents. Even now, according to Mrs Inglis, they still hanker after the
cards.
More recently, information providers have begun to publish their less
frequently changing information on CD-ROM.
Mrs Inglis subscribes to these services if the data is going to be accessed
frequently. Her job is to weigh the cost of the CD-ROM service against the
cost of pay-as-you-go on-line services. In the case of Kompass and CD
Europa, for example, the CD-ROM option has been chosen. Twelve disks are
provided through the year and the two services cost Pounds 3,000 and Pounds
15,000 respectively. CD Europa provides Dun &amp; Bradstreet reports for the
whole of Europe.
OTHER CD-ROM information sources include: Disclosure - information on US
companies, SEC registrations, quarterly reports etc; Moody's International;
Standard and Poor's stock reports - historical information about share
price, dividend record, balance sheet and profit and loss; and Lotus One
Source - the IDD Mergers and Acquisitions database. Hoare Govett used to
take the IDD information on-line, but it was a long-winded process and the
telephone connection kept breaking.
The company also has a personal computer dedicated to the Amdata mergers and
acquisitions database. Once a month, Amdata squirts its updates over the
telephone where they are stored in the hard disk of this dedicated machine.
Monthly CD-ROM disks are preferred, however, because these take up a tiny
fraction of the room needed by a dedicated PC.
Hoare Govett uses a range of conventional on-line information services,
spending approximately Pounds 10,000 a year on Dun &amp; Bradstreet's Dunsprint
on-line service. This provides information on unquoted companies around the
world, especially north and south America, and is a useful way of finding
out about company subsidiaries.
For UK companies, because Companies House is just around the corner, it is
more convenient to use the Chorus on-line ordering service and a few minutes
of a messenger's time. For just Pounds 3, Mrs Inglis can obtain a microfiche
record of a company's memorandum and articles of association and at least
five years' worth of annual reports and other financial information.
FOR press information the company accesses Reuters' Textline through the FT
Profile service. Searches can be refined by subject matter, by industry and
by geography. The service provides very sophisticated search options and
delivers a list of headlines which meet the criteria. The user decides from
this list which articles or synopses should be downloaded to Hoare Govett.
The monthly cost of this service is Pounds 5,000, before any volume
discounts have been applied.
Other on-line services used include: Extel Workstation - historical company
financial information; Dialog - an umbrella, or host, service which gives
access to hundreds of databases through a consistent user interface. (While
this saves users from having to learn many different access methods, it does
result in a loss of flexibility, especially with a sophisticated system like
Textline); Thomson Financial Services' Investext - brokers' reports on
quoted companies; and Perfect Information - press cuttings, company news,
company circulars and press releases.
Perfect's services are unusual because they give users access to images of
the original documents. These are held on optical disc juke-boxes at Perfect
Data's premises. Because Perfect Information is used so heavily, Hoare
Govett accesses the service over a tied telephone line.
Datastream and Extel are accessed over tied lines for the same reasons. In
order to keep a control of the costs of these two services, the company pays
a flat rate for each one. Pay-as-you-go systems are best operated by skilled
users, otherwise costs can spiral out of control. The alternative is to pay
a fixed sum and let users do their worst.
As a rule of thumb, the power of the search tools is in inverse proportion
to the friendliness of the user interface. Datastream, which can be
difficult to use, can for example, provide sophisticated graphing facilities
based on the users' own equations.
Mrs Inglis would like to see the flat-rate and CD-ROM information services
delivered to the users' desktops across the company's networks. As people
move up the company they become more reluctant to use the keyboard, but the
Windows environment overcomes some of these difficulties. One of the
problems for users is that most information services differ in how the
information is accessed. There is a clear limit to how many different
methods the user can be expected to learn.
CD-ROM and on-line systems vastly increase the range of accessible
information, on offer, however, and this is their great advantage. ' At
Hoare Govett, for example, a research analyst wanted a breakdown of the
population of California by sex age and racial origins. Mrs Inglis knew of a
database that could help - Donnelly Demographics. She dialled in and within
five minutes delivered the information to an astonished analyst.
She points out that you cannot afford not to get what your competitors have
got. She also notes that electronic information can be downloaded easily
into spreadsheets and other documents. Some software packages are now
available which do all the work - they dial the service, download the
information and integrate it into your applications. Information Partners
from New Information Paradigms is a good example. On-line and CD-ROM
information frees up skilled library staff for much more sophisticated
information provision.
In the future, Mrs Inglis would like to connect these sources of information
directly into the company's computer networks. Instead of a printout,
information would be delivered directly to the user's screen. This kind of
service would enable the end users to become much more accurate and precise
in finding their own information.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XVIII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-2779</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CLKB5AH5FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921210
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / Survey of Software at Work - Winter 1992 (21): Afloat in a
rough sea - Leasing application / How on-line data helps reach balanced
underwriting decisions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID TEBBUTT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WITH SO MANY companies going out of business or falling down on repayments,
it is not easy for a leasing company to choose the right customers, writes
David Tebbutt.
Schroder Leasing, which leases office and medical equipment, owes its
continued good health at least in part to its astute use of on line database
information.
'Not only does the information enable us to reach balanced underwriting
decisions, it has helped us to give our supplier network a more rapid
response to proposals,' says James McWattie, general manager. These benefits
have helped Schroder Leasing to maintain acceptable profitability through
one of the worst crises in the sales aid leasing business.
Mr McWattie uses financial, status and overview reports from ICC, depending
on the level of information needed. Financial reports include balance sheet,
and profit and loss.
Status reports give details of smaller companies, which do not have to file
full accounts. The financial or status report is accessed for deals in
excess of Pounds 10,000, while the overview report is generally sufficient
for smaller deals.
Another key source of information is the county court judgment database
which has recently been added to the ICC service. This often gives an
indication that something is going wrong in a company.
Once all the information is in, it is combined with other details such as
the type of business, how long it has been trading and the industry it is
in. Decisions can be made rapidly, providing the source information is
comprehensive and up to date.
BEFORE subscribing to the ICC service, Schroder Leasing relied on bank
reports, county court judgments and lower level reports from other
information providers and, sometimes, hard copy accounts which took up to 48
hours to arrive. The most-used report was Infolink's CMS4 which lists
financial transactions on a company's file. This information is supplied by
contributing members, such as finance houses and leasing companies.
These methods were slow and inaccurate. If Schroder Leasing wanted to go
into more detail on a company's circumstances, the delay could have meant
the competition getting the deal.
The recession has made it even more important to gain up-to-date
information, and was another factor in looking for a more effective way of
working.
ICC's on-line database information was the first step. The system currently
contains details on every single limited company, with full details on more
than 360,000. These company records cover some 70 per cent of Schroder
Leasing's business. It does, however, lack detail on sole traders and
partnerships, the remaining 30 per cent. For this type of client, the
company relies on UAPT Infolink and bank opinions.
Schroder Leasing chose ICC because it offers first class data at a
competitive price. Other on-line services and CD-ROMs considered were
rejected for being inaccurate, out of date or for containing details of too
few companies.
In addition to filtering out bad risks, the on-line services have allowed
Schroder Leasing to take on new business in risky sectors, by providing a
clear view of a potential client's financial performance.
For a selection of database services: see pages 19 and 20
</TEXT>
