<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / Survey of Software at Work - Winter 1992 (19): Information
at your fingertips - David Tebbutt examines the latest ways to access
business data via the computer terminal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID TEBBUTT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TIMELY access to information can mean the difference between success and
failure, or life and death. At one extreme, the recent failures in the
ambulance service computer system in the UK show the serious consequences of
information loss. At the other end of the scale, a businessman may want to
find out as much as possible about a client before extending a line of
credit.
In a more leisurely age, a 48-hour wait for a photocopied document would not
have made much difference to a business relationship. Nowadays, a 48-minute
wait could result in the business going elsewhere.
The computer could well be the cause of life speeding up to today's hectic
levels. But it has also provided the tools to help cope with new demands
placed upon us.
Worldwide, direct-dial telephone networks have not only transformed our
ability to make contact, they have enabled computers to talk to each other,
too. Any information residing in any computer anywhere on this planet could,
theoretically, be passed to any other. The only requirement is a connection
into the ever-expanding international telecommunications web.
Many companies around the world have recognised the value of the information
they own and have made it available to computer systems and computer
terminal users. These on-line information services present callers with
menus on their computer screens from which they can call up information
which interests them.
You can, on a news clipping service, for example, ask for all mentions of
IBM, in the computer press, in western Europe, in the last three weeks. On a
financial data service, you might ask for IBM's financial results for the
last five years, and details of company officers during that period.
These on-line services are useful for both rapidly-changing and historical
information. Compact discs, just like those used to play music, hold huge
amounts of digital information. A dozen songs is about the equivalent of
600m characters of information. Not surprisingly, therefore, discs have been
seen as another publishing opportunity.
Historical and slow-moving information is well-suited to this medium, so a
regular information-browser might find it cheaper to get a year's worth at
one go on a single CD-ROM, rather than repeatedly use expensive on-line
databases. Some statistical data, such as the UK's 1981 Census, will never
change, so the CD-ROM publication is more like an interactive book. Some
CD-ROM publishers produce cumulative discs every month - or every three
months - leaving the user to go on-line for any data in the intervening
periods. The problem with all these different sources of information is that
each provider has its own access methods. But knowing how to use one
database is no guarantee that you can use another. To overcome this problem,
a number of companies have developed access systems which are consistent
across different databases. Subscribers to Dialog, for example, can gain
access to other providers' databases through the same interface. They may
not, however, be able to use some of the more esoteric functions, when
connected.
Some software companies will develop systems which automate access to remote
databases. They can be triggered by the addition of, for example, a new
prospect record. If the customer was an individual looking for a loan, the
computer system might check address details, current loans, county court
judgments, employer details, and so on. A lot of vital information can be
brought to the user's attention in this way.
None of these information products and services is cheap, although a
fifteen-month archive of The Independent at Pounds 299 sounds pretty good
value. If access is required only infrequently, the best advice is to sign
up for an umbrella service, such as Telecom Gold or Dialog, where payment is
for connection time to the service. Heavier users might instead subscribe
directly to the service and seek a discount on access charges.
Other ways of keeping costs down are to go for a fixed-fee, unlimited access
arrangement, to buy CD-ROMs or to get periodic downloads of information
directly into hard disk drives.
Another area of expense is the telephone line. For heavy users, a dedicated
line direct to the information provider may be worth while. The trick is to
be as clear as you can about your information requirements before looking
for a service, and then to make sure that any deal can be changed, should
requirements alter.
If competitors are using on-line and CD-ROM services to improve performance
of their core business, then others have no choice. If they are not using
the services, or are using them unimaginatively, then this is an opportunity
to get one jump ahead.
The Online Business Sourcebook claims to be the only evaluative guide to
online database information. It deals with the full range of businesses in
one volume, including US data, although the emphasis is on UK and European
services.
The Sourcebook describes and evaluates a selection of 57 hosts and 779
electronic databases, including 130 on CD-ROM. It also indicates the most
recent connect time costs for Costs of the most commonly used hosts -
Dialog, FT Profile and PFDS - and others where known.
Updated twice yearly, the Sourcebook is available from Headland Press,
Cleveland, Tel 0429 231902. Headland also publishes a monthly newsletter,
Online Business Information; Online Business Sourcebook: ISSN 0953-5055.
User reports on database services appear on the following three pages.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XVII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-2781</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CLKB5AH3FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921210
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / Survey of Software at Work - Winter 1992 (20): Drawings at
high speed - Architectural applications / CAD, User Views
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
'WE work for the car industry and when they want something, they want it
right away,' says Mr Alexander Evans, partner in the Coventry-based
architects Hellberg Harris Partnership, who realised four years ago that in
order to produce and adapt their drawings very quickly, the 10-strong
company needed CAD technology. 'We wanted something to help us produce
drawings, adapt them, and prototype so that we could 'walk through' designs
with clients.'
Computervision, Intergraph and AutoCAD were on too grand a scale or not
close enough to architectural needs for the partnership. They wanted
something intuitive and GUI-based and found that the Architrion package,
hosted on the friendly Macintosh computer, met a all their needs.
'We chose Architrion because it is designed for architects and by them,'
comments Mr Evans. 'It works in the way we think.'
Consultancy How and Marshall (now KRCS) supplied Architrion II version 5.5,
running on a pair of Mac IIs, running 19-inch mono and colour monitors -
about Pounds 4,000 each - plus another Pounds 4,000-worth of printers and
plotters. The entire system was installed for Pounds 20,000 and has been
kept up to date with software upgrades and such extras as the Codec
estimating and pricing software. Another advantage of taking this
comparitively cheap route was the integration inbuilt in the Mac host:
information can be swapped between word processing and desktop publishing
applications - 'we can also take measurements from a disc from surveyors,
for example, through the DXF translator.'
Mr Evans is clear about the advantages: 'It's made us more efficient. We've
obtained and retained clients just by offering a quick service. The
interesting thing is that the client has a choice: we can do the job faster
at a cheaper rate, or charge the same for a more in-depth work. Without
exception they choose the cheaper route.'
Friar House, Coventry, (see picture on back page) was developed with 3D 'as
built' drawings, allowing high speed communication between consultants and
clients, before plans are finalised.
PRODUCT PROFILE
Architrion
Product: The Apple Macintosh version of Architrion, now on release 5.5, has
been available in the UK for six years. The latest version for PCs was
launched in February 1992, for which IBM holds sole marketing rights. It can
be used in conjunction with Codec Computer Operated Quantifying and Pricing
Software Release 1. Codec-Estimate, release 1, was launched in October 1992
in conjunction with IBM. It generates from Architrion CAD software the
elements of a building, presenting scheduling and pricing information in
bill-of-quantity format.
Suppliers: Architrion PC is available through IBM authorised dealers. Codec
Facilities, developers of Codec-Estimate, is a UK company founded in March
1992.
Number of users: 12,000 Macintosh users (350 in UK), 4,000 PC users
worldwide (Architrion).
Price: Pounds 1,995 plus VAT for Architrion PC/PS version; Pounds 2,255 plus
VAT for Codec-Estimate.
Hardware and operating systems: IBM PS/2 plus colour monitor, maths
co-processor and other 486 extensions for Architrion PC/PS.
Sales and support/ maintenance: Architrion is available from authorised IBM
dealers, yet to be appointed for Codec-Estimate. Codec supplies both
products. They make no software maintenance charge, hardware comes with free
parts and labour in first year. Software updates cost Pounds 300 pa;
training costs Pounds 350 a day.
User views: 'Low cost option, tailored for architects, ideal for small
practices, easy to use.'
Contact: Dennis Caldwell, Codec Facilities, Leamington Spa. Tel 0926 330112.
