<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / Survey of Software at Work - Winter 1992 (17): How to see
through a dark glass lightly - Manufacturing user view / A new design makes
a better impression in the right setting. CAD software has helped United
Glass improve its presentation.
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLAIRE GOODING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A new design makes a better impression in the right setting. CAD software
has helped United Glass improve its presentation. THE BOTTLES in which you
buy gin, beer or babyfood are 'fashion items' to the people who make them.
United Glass, a Pounds 177m company in St Albans, Hertfordshire, designs and
manufactures bottles for Guinness' Kaliber, and Heinz babyfoods, among other
customers.
'For 30 or 40 years, we've manufactured glass containers, but these days
glass is basically a fashion medium,' explains Ian Peake, design service
manager at United Glass. 'So much so that we couldn't go on selling using
two-dimensional drawings: we had to do something about our presentation and
visualisation to secure tomorrow's business.'
United Glass wanted a CAD product that related directly to glass design, so
it used a 'benchmark' project of a design to send to eight or so software
suppliers, including Prime, McDonnell Douglas, Intergraph, and others - 'our
priorities were presentation, accuracy, dedication, speed. It's important to
represent and render the true geometry of the bottles so that we can't
design something we can't make.'
Mr Peake discovered that the IDEAS product from SDRC was able to drive the
model using true dimensions, and also render the picture art speed.
High-speed visualisation was a must when presenting to clients, and some of
the other options lost out on their lack of speed, and the fact that they
needed dedicated proprietary hardware.
Communications Arts, a specialist in visualisation systems, won the Pounds
0.5m contract. It designed, installed and integrated the entire system,
using 18 Silicon Graphics workstations, two personal Iris computers and 15
Iris Indigos, plus print and plotting hardware from HP, Tektronix and Iris.
The main IDEAS software modules in use are the Wavefront Advanced
Visualiser, for rendering, animation and presentation, and the Alias Full
Color design and publishing system. The scope of the system reaches far
beyond the moving of presentation models in real time. There are links to
production systems to create moulds, and links to the sales and marketing
systems which produce pictures ready-made for glossy brochures.
As well as integrating all the CAD products so that they could exchange data
and dimensions, Communications Arts produced a number of 'scenarios.' United
Glass users can pick a number of scenes from a menu, and demonstrate the
designs to clients 'in situ,' with the backdrop of a pub interior,
supermarket or kitchen. These scenes can be 'edited' and adapted by users.
They also have a menu from which they can pick from a range of glass colours
and transparencies, with bottle contents ranging from ketchup to whisky in
viscosity.
SPEED is still an issue, given the complexity of the images produced by the
system - 'basically we binned everything we had and started from scratch. It
has taken a year, and we've spent Pounds 1m integrating with the mainframe,'
explains Mr Peake. 'It's really only when you take something on board and
use it that you discover such limitations as the size of files.'
Nevertheless, he declares himself 80 per cent satisfied with the system.
His words of warning to others researching CAD is to be wary of
salespeople's claims, especially regarding performance. 'Expectations can be
too high: we learned a a great deal in the process.'
PRODUCT PROFILE
Visualisation
System Suppliers: Communication Arts, a computer graphics system integrator
and and consultancy, was founded in the UK in 1989 by Pam Fisher, co-founder
of IBM reseller, P&amp;P Micro. It supplies computer technology for the
visualisation and origination of full colour material for print, animation
and other visual material.
Product: The high definition Visualisation System comprises equipment from a
total of seven leading manufacturers, integrated to create design drawings,
visualisation and output direct to film, print or VTR.
Turnover: Pounds 3m.
Price: Pounds 500,000 for typical installation hardware and operating
systems: Silicon Graphics workstations under Unix.
User views: 'Open systems platform has price advantages; integration service
excellent, but complexity of image work may mean early upgrades to
hardware.'
</TEXT>
