<PROFILE>_AN-CLKB5AH0FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921210
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / Survey of Software at Work - Winter 1992 (18): Importance of
clear objectives - Engineering application
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLAIRE GOODING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CAD software was initially bought as an engineering and drafting tool at
Hotpoint, the UK manufacturer of white goods. But now, according to David
Ellis, IT co-ordinator, 'it is an enabling-tool to improve the design to
manufacture process.'
Eight years ago the company chose Intergraph's EMS engineering modelling
system.
When a review looked in 1990 at alternative offerings from Computervision,
IBM and HP, Hotpoint decided that it still had the right tool, and stayed
with EMS. It now runs EMS, MicroStation, project layout and associated
desktop publishing products on a network of Intergraph UNIX workstations and
servers.
'There were many excellent solutions available, but CAD must be seen as an
integral part of the IT strategy, not an isolated tool, to get the maximum
benefit,' says Mr Ellis.
Hotpoint was looking for several different levels of integration - not just
in-house, but in dealing with third parties without having to translate. It
also put a high rating on useability and friendliness.
The system has now percolated most areas of Hotpoint, and plays a part not
only in the design, but in the manufacture, and even the user manuals
provided with Hotpoint's fridges, washing machines and dishwashers. There
are now links with the MRP manufacturing software, and with the CNC
numerical control systems in Hotpoint's Welsh factories in Rhyl and
Gwynnedd.
Mr Ellis stresses that the benefits have not been solely in the design
improvements attributable to CAD software, but in the new approaches that
its use has brought. His advice to others is that 'companies should look at
the processes, the people, and then at the technology as an enabler.' CAD
should help to develop and improve the effectiveness of individuals, and
also benefit and improve the process itself.
Too often, he warns, the implementation of CAD software fails because the
objectives have not been fully understood - 'the goals have to be defined
properly,' he concludes.
PRODUCT PROFILE
EMS Suppliers: Intergraph UK, owned by US Intergraph Corporation, founded in
the US in 1969, and in the UK in 1980.
Product: EMS, first launched in 1986, and updated by Version 2 in 1992, is
an integrated solid-surface modelling and drafting system.
Microstation version 4, first launched 1986 and updated to version 4 by
1991, is a general purpose 3D design-2d drafting package for PCs, Apple Macs
and UNIX workstations. GUI-driven, the product provides true associative
dimensioning, hot links to database and powerful workgroup facilities.
Turnover: Dollars 1.2bn worldwide, with Dollars 71.1m profit in 1991 (UK:
Pounds 42m with Pounds 2.2m profit).
Employees: 300+ in the UK
Number of users: 5,000 in UK, 160,000 worldwide
Price: Pounds 3,650 to Pounds 18,250 for EMS (modular), and Pounds 2,950 for
Microstation.
Hardware and operating systems: Intergraph InterPro UNIX workstations, Sun
Sparcstations, Silicon Graphics UNIX workstations.
Sales and support/maintenance: UK network of independent Intergraph
Solutions Centres. Maintenance is at 8-10 per cent of systems price, per
annum.
Other services available: customer training, project management, consultancy
and design, network design and installation and power supply surveys.
Custom software development, hardware maintenance, installation and
relocation is also available.
User views:
Pros: 'Integration, user friendliness.'
Cons: 'Too costly, too grand a scale, not focused on specialist needs,
hardware costs.'
Contact: Intergraph UK, Delta Business Park, Swindon, Wilts, Tel 0793 619999
</TEXT>
