<PROFILE>_AN-CLKB5AHYFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921210
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / Survey of Software at Work - Winter 1992 (15): Lansing gets
it right first time - Manufacturing View
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLAIRE GOODING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BEING 'right first time, more often' was the aim of Lansing Linde in
acquiring its CAD software. Lansing, based in Basingstoke and employing
2,000 people, is a well-known name in the manufacture of warehouse handling
equipment, particularly lift trucks, writes Claire Gooding.
It was a privately owned company known as Lansing Bagnall until its
acquisition in 1989 by the German company Linde, which specialises in
counter-balanced engine trucks.
'What we were looking for was the flexibility of bringing products to the
marketplace more quickly', explains Brian Cayley, senior executive engineer.
In 1983 the company assessed around 50 suppliers of CAD software, from
mainframe to PC hosts.
By the time Linde bought Lansing in 1989, there was already substantial
investment in two products: Computervision at Lansing, and Intergraph at
Linde. There are 12 Intergraph seats and 18 Computervision seats currently
in use. Rather than start from scratch, the company aimed to integrate its
existing software in a Computer Integrated Manufacturing (CIM) strategy
embracing CAD, CAM, CAPP, MRP and shop floor control systems. It chose CPlan
from CADCentre as the next step in Computer Aided Process Planning. Chassis
manufacture was selected for the trial as the most complex and variable
component.
CADCentre's contract, worth Pounds 90,000, included hardware, training, and
support. The CPlan software was first installed in 1988 and currently
supports 12 seats running on Sun workstations. The trial has been so
successful that the techniques learned in implementing CIM are to be used in
a new manufacturing plant being built in Basingstoke.
Four years ago, it took 12 weeks to complete the product after receiving an
order. Now, with the help of CPlan's CAPP techniques, it takes only four
weeks.
Lansing takes integration seriously. It has a direct Electronic Data
Management (EDM) link with its Blackwood plant, and its CAD facilities are
linked with its MRP and manufacturing packages, its machine control, and
even its technical publications.
'We take a wide view of the benefits', says Mr Cayley. In his opinion,
companies investing in 3D software should look for more than an increase in
drawing productivity, however dramatic. 'There are tremendous productivity
benefits in going from 2D to 3D, but you can find find yourself in a trap:
it doesn't necessarily better design. The current convention is to produce a
drawing, but CIM involves more than that.'
He points to several benefits in having invested so much in technology - 'it
gives us the ability to explore alternatives quickly, and to optimise our
designs. With the levels of ever-closer integration, we are going down the
road of parallel engineering.'
PRODUCT PROFILE
CPlan
Product: CPlan is a Computer Aided Process Planning product, for the
manufacturing process. Usages might include selection of the most
appropriate sequence of shop floor operations and creation of instructions
for the manufacturing department .
Suppliers: Developed and supplied by Cambridge-based CADCentre, originally
funded by the UK government's Ministry of Technology in 1967. Now in its
25th year, it is a profitable private sector company, with shareholders
including ICL; Cambridge University, St John's College, Cambridge, and
engineering consultancy WS Atkins. It has offices in the US and Germany.
Turnover: Pounds 9.3m with Pounds 861,000 profit in 1991-2; Pounds 8.3m,
with Pounds 32,000 profit in 1990-91,
Employees: 134 in the UK; 20 elsewhere
Users: 15,00 users in more than 1,000 companies in 30 countries worldwide.
Price: Pounds 10,000 for CPlan primary licence on single terminal, Pounds
6,000 for subsequent user seats.
Hardware and operating systems: UNIX and a number of proprietary operating
systems.
Sales and support/maintenance: direct from CADCentre, maintenance dependent
on configuration.
Other services available: seminars, training, and management consultancy,
including project management.
User views: 'Easy to use and flexible; supports integration with existing
computer systems.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XIV
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-2786</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CLKB5AHXFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921210
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / Survey of Software at Work - Winter 1992 (14): Higher
productivity with lower cost - Architectural user view
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLAIRE GOODING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ARCHITECTS at Yakeley Associates need high quality graphical presentations
to impress a varied customer base. In the public sector alone, Yakeley's
tasks can vary from the refurbishment of an office block to the creation
from start to finish of a Pounds 45m courthouse.
Like many architectural firms, Yakeley faced the problem of productivity.
With a staff of 18 and a turnover of about Pounds 700,000, the company saw
computer-aided design as a way of increasing efficiency and improving
presentation skills, without having to spend a crippling amount on
technology.
Just as important was the time and effort that would have to be invested in
learning, so easy-to-use software was a high priority.
'The advent of the Macintosh made the technology affordable for us,'
comments town planner Ian Kime.
'We originally bought our Mac for word processing, but started to invest in
drawing packages.'
Yakeley looked at Macdraft, and other contemporary offerings, including
AutoCAD and Architrion, but settled for a US-based package, MiniCAD. The
Yakeley team was unimpressed by what it saw as unnecessary complexity.'
He adds: 'The MiniCAD package was straightforward, and used the Mac
interface very well. In addition, it was one-quarter the price of anything
else we looked at.
'Since we installed the system in 1986, the software has developed and we
have also developed with it. The primary aim is to get the lines on the
paper as cheaply and efficiently as possible - nothing else really matters.'
THE Yakeley users are all self-taught novices, more at home with the
Architects Journal than the computer trade press. However, Ian Kime has been
quick to spot ways in which the use of CAD software can further benefit the
practice.
'Compatibility is critical in relation to the construction industry today,'
he says. 'The one thing we have to do is to talk electronically with other
consultants, exchanging drawing files with structural engineers and
consultants.'
MiniCAD allows them to exchange data through a Data Exchange Facility, DXF,
so that details of drawings can be taken off disc, worked on, and returned
in their original for mat. This saves errors in copying, and time in
reproducing data.
Although MiniCAD has speeded up the production of drawings, especially when
dealing with features that are repeated many times in one building, its
benefits have been much more widespread. They include the ability to target
and present services better, for example in the customisation of brochures
produced for a particular market sector.
'We have expanded our range of services,' says Mr Kime. 'We don't wait for
people to knock on our door, we take a pro-active approach, developing the
client's needs, defining them, and developing the brief with the client.
Essentially, the computer allows us to prototype buildings.
His colleague Mr Yeates agrees that there have been benefits in focusing the
architects' talents on the client's specific needs. 'We can now model all
the important parameters, and suggest the best building for the particular
conditions, focusing on the particular needs of that site or contract.
'Also, the technology affects the discipline and working procedures, keeping
track of who is working on what.
'Productivity is greater - which is good for our clients - because we can
produce more drawings for the same price.'
PRODUCT PROFILE
MiniCAD Suppliers: Diehl Graphsoft, developer of MiniCAD, was founded in the
US in 1985. Gomark, in London SW6, distributes the product in the UK.
MiniCAD can be used as a 2-D draughting package, or in 3-D to design,
visualise and present entire schemes.
It can be used as a basis for analytical studies in design. MiniCAD+ Version
4.0 was launched in 1992 by its US-based developer, Diehl Graphsoft.
The system combines easy-to-use classic 2D drafting, interactive modelling,
built-in spreadsheet and database tools with high-quality graphic output and
the ability to export data to other programs and systems.
Price: Pounds 595 plus VAT
Hardware and operating systems: Apple Macintosh
Sales and support/ maintenance: Available in the UK from Gomark. Other
services include training, available shortly from Gomark.
User views:
Pros: 'Low cost, easily integrated with other applications.'
Cons: 'Needs a great deal of storage capacity.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
