<PROFILE>_AN-CLKB5AHWFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921210
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / Survey of Software at Work - Winter 1992 (11): Never say no
to a rock star - User Report, Fisher Park / How computer software helps to
create three-dimensional fantasies for live musical events where demanding,
last-minute changes are the order of the day
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLAIRE GOODING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MARK FISHER and Jonathon Park may spend days discussing requirements
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
sketching, designing and building a stage set for a musical event. But it's
all change at the last minute if the massive design doesn't have the right
'feel' for the megastar client once it is built, regardless of cost and
wasted effort.
At the office of Fisher Park in Kings Cross, London, the details stored on
its small network of CAD screens are essential to the fast turnaround of
their work. They enable the company to adapt existing designs, pull in the
details of various stadium venues, and test the designs for 'buildability'.
In Fisher Park's somewhat off-beat line of business, fantastic ideas have to
be translated into workable, often mobile, structures. These have to be
built with regard to public safety regulations - and, just as important,
they must be designed to be broken down, packed into a truck, transported,
and rebuilt within the strictures of the next venue, wherever that is,
without exhausting the production crew.
'Although we call ourselves 3D designers,' says Mr Park, director, 'We are
really architects working in rock and roll. We deal with the client, take
the brief, visualise it, supervise the construction and implementation. We
are very much leaders and drivers of the project, although we're invisible
on the night.'
Their CAD system, Autodesk's AutoCAD running on a small PC network, is used
as an 'electronic pen', speeding up some of the tedious but precise design
work needed to realise the sketches resulting from brainstorming sessions
with the rock star.
Further down the line, they have to fulfil the normal duties of an
architect, providing working details to the crew who have to build and break
down the set and lighting equipment.
Fisher Park is the stage-set design company for rock concerts and
world-touring megastars. A newly-published book charts the progress of their
work: Sutherland Lyall's Rock Sets is full of photographs and CAD drawings
of such rock spectacles as Roger Waters' The Wall in Berlin, all designed by
Fisher Park.
Things have changed since the early days in 1966 when the Beatles played at
the Shea stadium in New York, packed with screaming fans who could hardly
see them. The current vogue for son et lumiere extravaganzas calls for a
combination of inspirational and practical design skills, plus the ability
to get on with temperamental rock stars. Something has to happen on stage
all the time to entertain and dazzle the audience.
Fisher Park has practically defined the business of mounting spectacular
live events. They met at (and still lecture for) the Architectural
Association. As a partnership, the pair has brought the professionalism of
mechanical and structural engineering to an essentially ephemeral,
theatrical business.
Having stumbled into it by accident with the rock group Pink Floyd in 1977,
their credits now include Pavarotti in the Park, Tina Turner's Foreign
Affair European tour, U2's Zoo TV Outside Broadcast US Stadium tour, and the
Rolling Stones' Steel Wheels tour.
It was Mick Jagger, the Stones' lead singer, who wanted a last-minute change
in their Urban Jungle set: overnight it was transformed from a green jungle
into a backdrop for a ravening dog.
The problem for Fisher Park is that the process of designing the sets is
very labour-intensive, and calls for a peculiar combinations of talent.
The process starts with a brainstorming session, which produces pen-and-ink
sketches, illustrating styles, narratives and thematic ideas, sometimes
produces from little more than a vague 'feel' or suggested atmosphere.
'The skill at this stage is in the sketches and the visualisation,' says Mr
Park. 'Our job is the technical realisation of the artiste's ideas. He or
she is the only begetter and creator. It is true that we can lead our
clients up paths they might never have explored, because we have experience
of the possibilities. But we also know the technical requirements and
limitations of touring and performing.'
Stage two involves design drawings such as technical elevations, and the
third stage has to provide working details. These must be precise for such
contractors as Scena and Brilliant Stages, London-based companies who
provide the building, electrical, lighting, carpentry and painting skills to
realise the designs.
The sets may cost between Pounds 1m and Pounds 2m but still represent only a
fraction of the production costs.
The team works closely with production experts on details of the tour
schedule and the needs of the crew in build and break-down phases. 'We all
work together as a team: we are the invisible member of it. If we don't
produce something workable, the stage crew will simply edit the set by
leaving parts of it behind as the tour proceeds.
'If they feel they own it - that they're part of the culture and the project
 -then they'll want to preserve the integrity of the idea.'
Using AutoCAD, the first two stages of design can take place more or less
simultaneously. As the sketches evolve from the ideas stage, they can be
drawn on screen and tested for practicality.
Another advantage is that the system can store a vast catalogue of re-usable
modular elements, such as Varilite searchlights which Fisher-Park first used
at the Seville Expo. The objects can be manipulated to fit new designs,
saving hours of detailed drawing time.
At one time, the company was tempted to try out Macintosh computers, but
decided to wait until AutoCAD, which they see as the standard architectural
computer tool, was available in 3D.
The company did not get computers until 1988 and now runs a three-seat
installation using Autocad release 11 - including desktop publishing
facilities - on Dell and Compaq work stations. They are planning to graduate
to release 12. Autodesk's 3D studio software allows them to animate the
designs.
Mr Park already had some experience of CAD software in his career at Ove
Arup. 'One issue was technical backup and reliability. It was reassuring
that AutoCAD had the biggest user base and a large user group. Many of the
drawbacks that had deterred us from computerising before were overcome in
later releases of the software.'
The main advantage has been in providing an extremely fast response to
ideas, but as Mr Fisher explains, the employment of technology has to be
appropriate.
'The drawings are only information. We have always produced more
comprehensive drawings because of our backgrounds. In fact, a hand sketch
can be more evocative because you're only limited by your talent and
imagination, it's not a matter of affording the technology. The computer is
only a tool to help you design: it's not a panacea, no substitute for a good
idea.'
Even as a workaday tool the software has its uses, for example imposing the
discipline of perspective. The company provides a professional engineering
approach, and the depth of detail. As with less transitory architecture,
each set is inspected and signed off at every stage. Its competitors -
largely from theatrical backgrounds - use computers, but not as a design
tool.
Fisher Park uses the 'struggle before you ask' principle, never having
attended an AutoCAD training course. They refer to the two-inch thick
manual, and rely on a friendly consultant firm Deus Ex Machina to provide
tailoring and comforting menus, the main complaint being that AutoCAD is so
complex that it is unfriendly, even for an habitual user.
The CAD images have been used with fully rendered computer animation to
produce a video based on the U2 rock spectacular. This acts as a showcase
for Fisher Park's skills: they would like to explore arenas beyond rock and
roll.
On a more mundane level, the software allows them to produce A4 images that
can be faxed to clients. As other organisations become CAD users, Fisher
Park finds further benefits. Now it can exchange AutoCAD details with the
lighting company Samuelsons, or pull in ready-made flatplan survey details
from another contractor, as they did for Seville Expo.
But the real pay-off is that the two directors are now able to manage the
workload without lots of staff producing technical drawings - 'in 1989 we
got rid of six drawing boards and put in three computers,' recalls Mark
Fisher. 'Now two of us do all the graft, and maintain a huge output. It's
easier to show people what we're talking about, and we can produce detailed
drawings very efficiently, but I couldn't say that's why they come to us.
They buy our ability to design, not to use computers.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
