<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / Survey of Software at Work - Winter 1992 (1): Importance of
software quality - Comment / Users have a right to some kind of independent
guarantee of quality and competence from software suppliers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNLIKE, say, a Faberge egg, software quality can be neither seen nor felt.
Where it is lacking, however, the consequences can range from simple
irritation to fatalities.
As an increasing proportion of the mechanisms which underpin our daily lives
 -from information systems to manufacturing robots - is passed over to the
computer, software quality issues are assuming a new and pressing
importance.
Mr Michael Heseltine, President of the Board of Trade, made it clear the
government is taking the issue seriously when last month he helped launch a
new award scheme for quality software. He said: 'Software quality is crucial
for the success of business and public services. The consequences of lack of
quality are being reported almost daily.'
Software failures make news when they involve massive disruption; banks
which are prevented from settling their liabilities, for example, or control
systems which permit accidents in nuclear power plants. But the less obvious
effects of lack of software quality are making themselves felt every day.
Stratus, the US manufacturer of fault tolerant computer systems recently,
attempted to estimate the effect of unplanned system downtime in UK
industry.
It calculated that the largest 1,100 organisations are losing approximately
Pounds 700m a year in revenues and productivity through computer downtime.
While hardware problems were responsible for 51 per cent of downtime, faults
in applications software, operating software and networking software could
be held to account for almost as large a proportion.
The question of software liability and economic loss is a legal grey area,
but Mr John Hull, specialist in intellectual property with the law firm
Wilde Sapte, provides persuasive reasons to suppose that 'it would be
ill-advised to assume there can never be liability for economic loss arising
out of defective software.'
Is, for example, a software error equivalent to a negligent mis-statement,
for which there is legal precedent for the award of damages?
In engineering terms, certainly, software is very strange stuff indeed.
Beyond a certain level of complexity it becomes very difficult to prove not
only that it will do what it is intended to do but that it will not do
something unexpected and untoward.
There have been a number of powerful improvements in the way the software
industry develops its products. These include mathematically-based formal
methods, software test harnesses and and computer aided engineering systems.
But these are essentially tools to take some of the risk out of the
developers' efforts.
Users have a right to some kind of independent guarantee of quality and
competence from software suppliers. What kinds of stamp of approval exist
already?
The starting point is BS 5750, the British Standard for Quality Systems, a
generalised model for a quality system. It is also the basis for
international set of quality standards ISO 9000. BS 5750 is industry
independent; it has nothing specific to say about software development, but
it does indicate that a customer should be able to expect consistent
delivery of high quality products and services on time and within budget
from a holder of the standard.
Neither has it anything to say about commercial practice. It is no
substitute for a legally binding contract in cases where a software supplier
fails to fulfill business obligations.
MR HESELTINE'S comments on software quality were made at the introduction to
an extension to the existing TickIT certification scheme, which is jointly
sponsored by the Department of Trade and Industry and the computer industry.
The scheme conforms to ISO 9001 and involves inspection by quality auditors
every three years. Introduced in 1991, it provides quality management
certification specifically tailored for the information technology industry.
The extension, the TickIT award for excellence, is sponsored by
International Business Machines. It is, however, a competitive scheme and
only four awards will be given each year - one each to small, medium and
large businesses and one to an in-house developer. The British Standards
organisation, however, is pressing beyond BS 5750 with a new scheme,
announced late last month, which will make possible 'kitemark' awards for
software packages - in the accounting area to begin with, but with the
intention of spreading the scheme to other sectors. Payroll is likely to be
next.
The British Standards Institute, which has itself no expertise in qualifying
software, is working with the consultancy KPMG which has been operating a
software quality centre in Boston, Massachusetts, for over a decade.
The test, which will cost company's between Pounds 15,000 for a pc product
and Pounds 50,000 for a mainframe system, will be in two parts. The BSI will
test for compliance with BS 5750, while KPMG will evalute the product to
ensure that it complies with a statrement of minimum functionality and that
it conforms to the description given by its suppliers.
'We are looking first to find software defects,' KPMG says. 'Then we seek to
determine the expected risk of software failure when tested is completed.
Finally, we categorise and summarise the defects uncovered during the
testing.'
KPMG points out it will be unable to guarantee there are no bugs in the
product, but once a package has been awarded the Kitemark, it will be
retested on an annual basis. One reason, according to KPMG, is that one in
three bug-fixes creates another bug. There are other, less formal,
indicators of quality. The Queen's Award for Technology or Export should
indicate a better than average product as should a Design Council Award.
There are a number of research studies, some of them funded by the European
Commission, into ways of ensuring that software is provably correct.
To date, there has been substantial progress although no real breakthroughs.
Perhaps there cannot be. But customers should demand that software products
meet at least a minimum level of functionality and should insist on an
authorised indication that that standard has been met.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
