<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / Bomb explodes near Tube station
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
A BOMB exploded yesterday evening in a car parked near Woodside Park
Underground station in north London. Scotland Yard said that vehicles were
damaged but nobody had been hurt. The station is above ground near the end
of the Northern Line.
The bomb exploded less than an hour after a coded telephone warning had been
given to the AP news agency by a man who said he was from the IRA. The
agency said the caller named Woodside Park, saying that a large device was
in position. The caller said there were '15 minutes to clear the station'.
Police evacuated the station and a nearby school and the Tube line near
Woodside Park was closed through the night for searches.
The scene of the blast is about a mile from Inglis Barracks where one
soldier was killed and nine injured in a bombing in August 1988.
Yesterday's blast follows the introduction of random police road checks in
central London and in Manchester, where 64 people were hurt in two blasts
last week. The IRA has threatened a Christmas bombing campaign on the
mainland.
</TEXT>
