<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / Top Clinton officials face tough ethics code:
President-elect may pick woman as attorney-general
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SENIOR officials in the incoming Clinton administration will be obliged to
sign an ethical code preventing them from ever lobbying a future US
government on behalf of foreign governments.
Members of the Cabinet and top deputies will be barred from lobbying their
former departments on behalf of domestic or foreign private-sector clients
for five years after leaving office. Senior White House officials will also
be subject to a five-year proscription from approaching departments for
which they had substantial responsibility.
Mr Warren Christopher, director of President-elect Bill Clinton's transition
team, said yesterday these were 'the strongest standards any president has
asked of his employees'. Current practice places a one-year lobbying ban on
former government employees, regardless of whether it is for domestic or
overseas interests.
The new code will apply to about 1,100 of the approximately 3,000 political
appointments Mr Clinton will be making in the months ahead. The first of
these may come today, as the economic policy team, headed by Senator Lloyd
Bentsen of Texas as treasury secretary, is due to be unveiled.
The New York Times reported yesterday that Mr Clinton was likely to choose a
woman as his attorney-general. This may reflect criticism that the likely
economic line-up is comprised exclusively of white males.
The four short-listed candidates for the Justice Department are Ms Patricia
Wald, a federal appeals court judge in Washington, Ms Amalya Kearse, who
holds a similar position in New York and who is seen as a potential Supreme
Court Justice when the next vacancy occurs, Ms Judith Kaye, a New York state
appeals court judge, and Ms Brooksley Born, a partner in Arnold and Porter,
a prominent Washington law firm.
In the course of the presidential campaign Mr Clinton said he was disturbed
by 'the revolving door between public service and private enrichment'. Mr
Ross Perot, the independent candidate, was even more damning. He claimed
foreign lobbyists, often former government officials, controlled the
Washington agenda.
However, in drawing up a code for his transition team Mr Clinton was obliged
to exempt from it such senior advisers as Mr Warren Christopher and Mr
Vernon Jordan, lawyers with extensive foreign and domestic public and
private-sector clients. Both had to agree, however, to suspend such
activities during the transition.
The permanent standards, to be embodied in an executive order signed by Mr
Clinton soon after he assumes office next month, will not exclude current or
former lobbyists from receiving posts in the administration. Medical and
scientific appointees, many of whom rely on government grants in their
professions, will be exempt from it, as will be career civil servants and
other former government officials hired for a different agency.
These exemptions are necessary so as not to deter well-qualified personnel
from joining the important middle ranks of the new administration.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 5
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-2811</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CLJCGAGVFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921210
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / Bush nominee advises against Iraq prosecutor
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE retired former New Jersey judge hand-picked by the Bush administration
to examine whether a special prosecutor should be named to investigate
possible criminal wrongdoing by administration officials in US dealings with
Iraq yesterday said there was no need for such an appointment.
Mr Frederick Lacey, a 72-year-old judge appointed to the bench under
President Nixon, concluded there had been no wrongdoing in officials'
handling of the Banca Nazionale del Lavoro (BNL) Iraqi loans scandal.
The judge's conclusions ignited criticism by leading congressional
Democrats, who called on President-elect Bill Clinton to investigate the
'Iraqgate' affair once in office.
Judge Marvin Shoob, who presided over the BNL Atlanta case, yesterday said
he was surprised and disappointed by Mr Lacey's recommendation because there
was 'ample evidence not only of a cover-up, but of government participation
that was improper'.
In remarks that at times sounded like an apologia for the Bush
administration, Mr Lacey claimed that 'many decent people have had their
careers tarnished and their reputations stained by being charged with being
part of a cover-up. These are baseless charges.'
Mr Lacey, echoing the view of Mr William Barr, the US attorney-general who
must decide on a special prosecutor, termed congressional charges of a
cover-up 'arrant nonsense'.
Judge Lacey's defence of the administration was curious as he informed Mr
Barr on October 26 that there were 'sufficiently specific and credible
allegations' to extend his inquiry. Instead, Mr Lacey yesterday blamed
congressional Democrats and the media for being irresponsible.
Mr Lacey, derided by some congressional critics as a 'patsy' for the Bush
administration, also gave his verdict on admissions by Central Intelligence
Agency (CIA) officials that they deliberately concealed from prosecutors in
Atlanta reports about the involvement of BNL's head office in Rome. He
claimed these were 'a series of mistakes by well-meaning and
well-intentioned persons'.
Mr Lacey served until 1985 as a member of the US Foreign Intelligence
Surveillance Court, a secretive body that makes decisions about authorising
wiretaps and other intelligence matters.
Mr Jack Brooks, the conservative Texas Democrat who chairs the House
Judiciary Committee which originally demanded a special prosecutor,
yesterday called upon the new Clinton Administration 'to see that justice is
done' in the investigation of US dealings with Iraq.
During the presidential campaign Mr Clinton supported calls for a special
prosecutor and Senator Al Gore, his running mate, said the Iraqgate affair
was 'bigger than Watergate' and required investigation.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
