<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / UK Company News: Costly newspaper bill for Murray Intl
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
A disastrous venture into newspaper publishing by Murray International
Holdings, the holding company controlled by Mr David Murray, a leading
Scottish businessman and chairman of Rangers football club, cost the company
Pounds 5.7m.
Murray International, whose main business is steel stockholding but which
also has interests in property, leisure and electronics, closed the Sunday
Scot tabloid in July 1991 after only five months.
The group, 88 per cent owned by Mr Murray, lost Pounds 1.54m in the year
ended January 31 1992 on sales of Pounds 165m (Pounds 135.5m). A loss of
Pounds 1.6m from the Sunday Scot as shown as an extraordinary item.
The results for 1991 showed a loss of Pounds 4.2m for the newspaper as an
exceptional item, although it occurred in the next financial year. In 1991
the group lost Pounds 5.4m.
Murray is transferring its property interests to Premier Property, a new
company with the same shareholders as Murray International.
</TEXT>
