<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow steady as IBM falls on
dividend fears
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US share prices were flat-to-lower in heavy trading yesterday as the market
consolidated some of its recent gains, writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
At the close the Dow Jones Industrial Average was up 1.63 at 3,323.81 below
its peak for the day when the index had been 13 points higher. The more
broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 ended its record-breaking streak with a
decline of 1.33 to 435.66 while the Amex composite gave up 1.67 at 392.98
and the Nasdaq composite slipped 3.20 to 663.92, off its all-time high.
Turnover on the NYSE was 231m shares, and declines outpaced rises by 1102 to
728.
Blue chips opened higher amid optimism about the economy and corporate
earnings but were unable to hold on to their gains in active two-way
trading.
The release of the Federal Reserve's 'Beige Book' report on nationwide
business conditions - had little impact on the market primarily because it
said little new about the economy, and was consistent with recent indicators
that have pointed to a moderate expansion in economic growth. The Fed's
surveys found a 'modest improvement' in economic activity, low inflation,
but continued weakness in manufacturing employment.
Equity investors were cheered by the reaction of the bond market, which
barely budged after the Fed's report was published. The bond market was
pleased that the Fed discovered no signs of resurgent inflationary pressures
in the economy. Investors will get a better indication of inflation today
and tomorrow when the November consumer and producer prices indices are due
to be released.
IBM fell Dollars 2 3/4 to Dollars 62 5/8 as the stock continued to suffer
from the predictions of two Wall Street analysts on Tuesday that the
computer giant will announce further restructuring moves that could hurt its
earnings. The warnings raised fears that the company's dividend might be
threatened.
Lockheed jumped Dollars 3 3/4 to Dollars 55 3/4 in busy trading after the
company concluded an agreement to buy General Dynamics' tactical military
aircraft business for Dollars 1.5bn in cash. General Dynamics, which is
expected to reap a net gain of about Dollars 650m from the deal, rose
Dollars 2 7/8 to Dollars 103 7/8 .
Bradlees fell Dollars 1 to Dollars 17 3/8 , Kmart dropped Dollars  1/2 to
Dollars 25 5/8 , May Department Stores eased Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 68 7/8
and JC Penney fell Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars 76 1/2 after the retailers, plus
many others, were downgraded by Merrill Lynch, the broking house, in
anticipation of a broad-based correction in retail stocks early next year.
Times Mirror dropped Dollars  3/4 to Dollars 30 after the securities house
First Boston cut its investment rating on the stock from 'hold' to 'sell'
because of concerns about soft advertising revenues at the group's
newspapers.
Dime Savings Bank rose Dollars  3/8 to Dollars 5 3/8 after the bank said the
Office of Thrift Supervision had lowered Dime's risk-based capital ratio
from 9 per cent to 8 per cent, which should free up some additional capital.
Canada
TORONTO stocks finished lower after a heavy trading session marked by the
strong performance of companies with properties near the Northwest
Territories diamond find.
Investors flocked to junior mining stocks which hold property in the
Northwest Territories after Dia Met Minerals and partner Broken Hill
Property Ltd announced promising drilling results yesterday .
The TSE 300 edged down 5.4 to 3,285.5 on volume of 45.9 million shares
valued at CDollars 337m.
</TEXT>
