<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / Money Markets: Cash flows tighten
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MONEY flows were tight yesterday as the clearing banks resisted early
temptations to take up the Bank of England's offers of assistance and
preferred to take short-term money rates instead, writes Peter John.
Consequently, overnight money, which began the day at just below 7 per cent,
was bought up to around 8 1/4 per cent before moving lower at the close. At
the higher levels, the central bank offers became attractive again and 80
per cent of the forecast liquidity shortage was taken out. Three-month money
remained stable at 7 1/8 per cent.
Sterling futures returned to more credible levels after looking
extraordinarily cheap for the past few days. The contract for March
delivery, which tends to be the most sensitive indicator of the way interest
rates could be heading was sold off at the opening, reflecting the sharp
downturn in the pound.
It rallied later to end the day 9 basis points up on the day at 93.50 with
relatively thin turnover of 14,000 contracts by the official close. At that
level it reaffirmed the market's belief that a further half a percentage
point could be lopped off the base rate soon.
Bank of England operations were cold-shouldered during the early part of the
day with no help provided in the morning and only Pounds 30m of the final
forecast of Pounds 1bn liquidity shortage taken up at noon.
Among the main factors affecting the shortage were the take-up of treasury
bills and paper maturing in official hands, expected to drain Pounds 827m
from the system, bankers' balances below target and a rise in note
circulation. These were partly offset by exchequer transactions adding
Pounds 210m.
At midday, the Bank bought Pounds 5m of band one bank bills at the 6 7/8 per
cent rate and Pounds 25m of bills for resale on January 5 at 6 7/8 per cent.
In the afternoon, the Bank bought Pounds 376m of band one and band two bank
bills, both at 6 7/8 per cent rate. It also bought Pounds 29m of bills for
resale on January 5 at 6 15/16 per cent. However, it was not until the
official close that the shortage was addressed and even then it was not
taken out. The Pounds 390m of late, unspecified assistance brought total
help to only Pounds 796m.
In Germany, call money was at 8.95 to 9 per cent in early trading. The
Bundesbank added DM6.5bn of liquidity to the banking system with its weekly
repo tender bringing the figure to DM77bn.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 37
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-2833</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CLJCGAF9FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921210
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / Foreign Exchanges: Pound records sharp correction
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
STERLING'S recent gains were wiped out yesterday as investors decided that
the time was ripe to pocket their profits, writes Peter John.
The bizarre situation of the past few days in which the pound has
strengthened with no visible sign of fundamental economic support and the
dollar has fallen in spite of repeated nuggets of positive news was
reversed.
In a thin pre-Christmas market many currencies have been moved purely by
technical factors with multi-national companies in particular said to have
been keen to buy back sterling in order to balance their books.
However, comments by two of the senior economists picked by the government
to sit on a new economic advisory panel were seized on as a signal to sell
sterling. One of the advisers, Prof Wynne Godley, has argued that base rates
should come down to 5 per cent and sterling needed to be devalued by a
further 15 per cent. This prompted heavy selling in the Far East and
sterling fell sharply against the dollar and D-Mark at the start of dealing
in London.
By midday, it had tumbled four pfennigs to just above DM2.45 and had lost
three cents against the dollar to hit Dollars 1.5639. Then, the
blood-letting was staunched and sterling rallied to close at DM2.4650 and
Dollars 1.5665.
There is a divergence of views in the market with some analysts arguing that
the recent rise had nothing to back it up and others seeing 10 pfennigs of
upside over the next month or so.
Merrill Lynch says longer-term investors and asset managers were 'severely
underweight' in sterling until last week and have not yet had time to adjust
their positions.
The dollar, on the other hand recovered from a few days of pressure prompted
by speculators with long positions selling the US currency to square those
positions.
Dealers said the speculative presure faded yesterday and genuine buying was
seen. The dollar recovered to DM1.5705 from DM1.5570 but it was stable
against the Yen and Panmure Gordon's chief economist Mr Robin Aspinall said
laconically in his latest strategy review; 'The US economy is moving so
fast, it is almost trundling'.
The D-Mark also lifted, picking up against most of the exchange rate
mechanism currencies. There is a general feeling that the Bundesbank will
not cut interest rates when it meets today and the D-Mark gained against the
lira, the peseta and the franc.
The French currency continued weak in spite of some suggestions that the
Bank of France had intervened.
At least one dealer was adamant that the central bank had been buying francs
and another said it had been dipping in and out of the market all day. But,
others said that either they had not seen any intervention or that the Bank
was simply checking prices. The franc slipped to a low of FFr3.414 against
the D-Mark before closing virtually unchanged at FFr3.411.
</TEXT>
