<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / Survey of Charity Fund Investment (9): Don't just sit back -
Andrew Jack examines the role of trustees
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHEN Kingsley Napley, a firm of solicitors, issued a booklet recently on the
legal duties of charity trustees it had no idea of the level of response
this would provoke. The firm's London office has since been bombarded with
telephone calls and written requests for copies.
At a time when the need for charity trustees to take their responsibilities
seriously has never been greater, the incident is an illustration of the
extent of current ignorance of their role. A recent survey by the National
Council for Voluntary Organisations showed that few charity trustees had a
clear view of their responsibilities. Only one-third of the members of
charity management committees were even aware that they were trustees.
Under present law, Britain's estimated 1m charity trustees have wide-ranging
legal, financial and managerial responsibilities. Of them all, the most
worrying is that a trustee could face personal bankruptcy in order to meet
outstanding debts incurred by the charity. This is true in spite of the fact
that trustees usually give their time voluntarily, with no thought of
personal gain. (In fact the law itself prevents them from receiving payment
for their labours.)
The 1992 Charities Act has added to existing obligations by including
additional requirements on financial reporting and annual auditing,
fund-raising and administration.
Mr Tony Sacker, head of the charities group at Kingsley Napley, says that
for the first time he is now dealing with several cases of charity trustees
who face personal legal action to recover funds.
'People's first reaction, when I tell them their obligations, is that I must
have got it wrong,' he says. 'They can't believe it.'
It is not so much that the new legislation has brought aggressiveness;
rather that there is increasing willingness by creditors (such as landlords
and banks) to take action to recover outstanding debts. Moreover, in an era
of declining government grants, charity trustees might even find themselves
liable for staff redundancy payments if they have to close or reduce the
operations of a charity.
'Trustee' may be more widely defined than those persons who simply have the
name attached. Trustees normally also include executive committee members
and, more widely, the council members who delegate powers to this executive.
Guidance on who are the trustees of a charity's assets comes from the legal
trust deed or memorandum which formally governs the charity.
But what action can trustees take to protect themselves against legal action
and personal liability? Mr Sacker says: 'When you realise you've got a
problem it's usually too late.'
The greatest protection for trustees, he says, is to act only for charities
which are limited by guarantee and governed by the requirements of the
Companies Acts. This grants to trustees a protection similar to that of
directors of companies, exempting them from personal liability.
But Mr Sacker says the catch is that few charities want to incur the
administrative difficulties or the audit and other costs of incorporation
when they are first created. And once a charity is running successfully,
trustees are equally reluctant to incur the additional burdens of
re-establishing their organisation as a corporation.
Charities which have sufficient assets to cover their liabilities - even if
that means curtailing their operations - will generally be able to liquidate
these before the need for trustees to dip into their own pockets would
arise.
The main safeguard for a trustee is not to enter into any commitments which
might result in personal liability.
For example, if the charity takes out a loan or a lease on premises, Mr
Sacker suggests that trustees should agree the ground rules in advance,
explicitly stating, in writing, that they are not willing to be made
personally liable.
As a rule, trustees are only liable for any commitments made once they join
a charity. If they sign a bank loan or a new lease without special
protection, they may leave themselves vulnerable to action. Normally they
will not be liable for actions made by previous trustees before they joined,
according to Mr Sacker. But they run this risk if they have signed an
indemnity to take on liabilities from out-going trustees when they first
join.
Even with all these safegaurds, trustees may still be vulnerable. 'In every
case you have to get into the detail,' says Mr Sacker. 'You could find
yourself responsible. These things appear to happen almost by accident.'
That leaves preventative action to ensure that a charity does not run into
financial difficulties in the first place. Kingsley Napley's book highlights
a number of points worthy of note by prospective trustees:
Ask to see the governing document of the charity.
Check the status of the charity and what it is entitled to do.
Meet the co-trustees and ask if they are following its purposes.
Find out what the charity's liabilities are and ensure they are covered by
assets.
Examine and get help in understanding the latest set of accounts, ensuring
they are informative and up-to-date.
Ask about any investments, in order to understand how well they are managed.
Mr Sacker stresses the need to keep the threat to trustees in perspective.
'I can't say the bankruptcy courts are bursting with charity trustees,' he
says. 'It probably will never happen to you. But don't just sit back and
assume that everything going on is fine.'
A guide to the legal duties of a charity trustee. Free from Kingsley Napley,
107-115 Long Acre, London WC2E 9PT
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 35
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-2841</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CLJCGAF0FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921210
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / Survey of Charity Fund Investment (6): The aim is to be a
household name - Competition between charities means that image is more
important than ever
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE is a growing fashion for charities to change their images and, in some
cases, their names.
Image is more important than ever in the climate facing the voluntary
sector. Charities are competing for donations, public-sector contracts,
top-quality managers and the services of voluntary workers.
In fund-raising terms, a household name is a precious advantage for a
charity. Changing it is one of the most risky decisions it is possible to
take, and is guaranteed to split active supporters. Some organisations are
nonetheless taking this ultimate step as part of re-launch programmes.
All charities have to be sensitive to the views of the groups they represent
and support. The acceptability of the language in which disability and
disadvantage are described changes over time, and some of the recent name
changes reflect this.
But another factor behind the spate of re-launches is the perceived need on
the part of charity managers to adopt sharp, modern images for their
organisations as the voluntary sector competes for contracts to deliver
public services.
Both these elements were illustrated in the re-launch of the Royal National
Institute for the Deaf earlier this year. The name change was a modest one -
it is now the Royal National Institute for Deaf People. This enabled the
institute to satisfy the growing concern of people with disabilities that
they should be represented as human beings rather than a detached, abstract
group while avoiding the problems of having to market an entirely new name.
The institute accompanied the change with a clear bid for contracts under
next year's community care reforms, saying that it intended to concentrate
in future on providing services as well as campaigning. A specialist
organisation like the institute, it said, was the 'best channel through
which local authorities and health authorities can meet demands for their
deaf and hard-of-hearing clients.'
In October the Royal Society for Mentally Handicapped Children and Adults -
better known as Mencap - became the next big charity to stage a re-launch.
The most striking visible evidence of this is the disappearance of Little
Tommy - the sketch of a sad-looking child that has been the society's logo
since the 1960s - and its replacement by a series of confident, successful
images of people with learning disabilities.
'One of the particular difficulties of re-launching a charity is that you
have to sell the new image inside the organisation as well as outside, and
it is not easy to please everybody,' says Steve Billington, Mencap's
director of marketing and appeals.
Some of the parents who founded Mencap in 1946 remain active in its ranks
today; a number are unhappy about the modern new image the charity is aiming
to project. An even bigger controversy than the removal of Little Tommy may
be yet to come - there is division within the ranks of Mencap over whether
its name should be changed. In today's climate some people feel that the
term mental handicap is inappropriate.
A similar argument last month led to another of Britain's best-known
charities - the Spastics Society - agreeing to change its name. The term
spastic is considered by many to be offensive to people with cerebral palsy,
and one that presents a negative image of their potential.
A decision to change the name and re-launch the society was agreed by a 4-1
majority at the society's annual meeting. The Spastics Society is one of
Britain's 30 biggest charities, and most of the opposition to the change
came from speakers who, while not regarding the name with any particular
affection, were worried about the possible fund-raising implications of
dropping its familiar title and image.
A short-list of possible new names will be voted on next year. Suggestions
so far have ranged from the straightforward Cerebral Palsy Association to
names like Scope and Capability which incorporate the initials CP.
Some name changes can be relatively gradual or subtle. The Church of England
Children's Society - originally the Waifs and Strays - now promotes itself
simply as the Children's Society. Queen Elizabeth's Foundation for the
Disabled, following the pattern of the RNID, has become Queen Elizabeth's
Foundation for Disabled People.
On other occasions, a more radical approach is adopted. Four years ago, the
National Marriage Guidance Council re-launched itself as Relate. The
decision did not win universal approval within the organisation, and the
internal debate over the new name has still not entirely died down.
Advocates of change were concerned that the former title gave the impression
that the council's services were available only to people who were legally
married - which was not the case - and that potential clients were being
discouraged from seeking counselling. Opponents argued that the name change
might suggest that the council no longer regarded marriage as a serious
institution - which it does - and that the organisation would lose its
national credibility and identify.
Four advertising agencies were invited to put forward proposals for a new
name. More conservative alternatives, like the Marriage and Family
Counselling Service, were considered before the final choice went to Relate.
Shortage of funds has prevented Relate commissioning market research into
the effects of the name change. There has been a 50 per cent increase in the
number of people seeking its services over the past five years, but no-one
knows to what extent this arises from Relate's new image and how much from
social factors.
Relate went into the name change with the advantages that much of its
funding comes from central and local government, and that it tends to
concentrate in its public fund-raising on one-off events such as charity
film premieres.
The financial risk of a name change is greater for charities that rely on
widespread general fund-raising. Many people can name only a handful of
charities; a lot of money collected in workplace raffles this Christmas will
be donated to chosen causes simply because they have names that everyone
knows. For this reason the Spastics Society has decided that, whatever new
name is chosen next year, it will initially be used in tandem with the
existing one.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 34
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-2842</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CLJCGAFZFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921210
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / Survey of Charity Fund Investment (8): Alarms and diversions
 -The national lottery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S first national lottery, in 1569, raised money to repair the Cinque
Ports. For the following 250 years lotteries regularly financed public works
and the Exchequer.
The historical precedent is not lost on leaders of Britain's voluntary
sector, who are apprehensive about government proposals to revive the
national lottery in a bill about to go before parliament. They have two main
anxieties: that it will divert money from other charity fund-raising
activities, and that lottery receipts paid to charities might eventually
replace other forms of public sector finance.
Furthermore, some charities have moral objections to the national lottery,
seeing it as state encouragement of gambling or even as a tax on the poor.
Surveys show that poorer people are likely to spend a greater proportion of
their income on lottery tickets, while some of the causes benefiting from
the lottery (such as the arts) are disproportionately patronised by higher
income groups.
The government apparently believes that the lottery might eventually achieve
an annual turnover of Pounds 4bn - at the high end of a range of estimates.
Once prize money and administration costs are deducted, the remaining
proceeds - probably less than one-third of total lottery income - would be
available for distribution to good causes. Such causes would include the
arts, sport, heritage and a special Millennium Fund for big projects, as
well as charities.
Charity managers are concerned that the public might buy lottery tickets to
support good causes and, as a result, withdraw from alternative forms of
charitable donation, without appreciating that the lottery proceeds were
going to sports projects and other activities that some people would not
regard as charitable. To compensate for the feared loss of income, a number
of the big charities have argued that half the proceeds available for
distribution should go to the voluntary sector.
Since the lottery is likely to go ahead, in spite of the concerns of charity
managers, the voluntary sector is now devoting its efforts to trying to
secure the most advantageous arrangements.
Two working parties - one set up by the National Council for Voluntary
Organisations (NCVO), the other by the Association of Charitable Foundations
(ACF) - have come to similar conclusions about the appropriate
organisational structure to administer the lottery. Government observers sat
on both working parties, and their reports are likely to influence future
decisions on the lottery.
Both reports call for a national board and regional structure, with separate
committees for England, Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland, to take
responsibility for making grants to charities from lottery proceeds.
A central theme of the reports is that awarding grants must be free from
government interference. Otherwise, says the NCVO, there would be a danger
of 'direct political control of allocation decisions by government' and an
increased risk that the lottery would gradually replace other public sector
funding.
The ACF says the distribution board should adopt a general policy statement
that 'lottery money will not substitute for government grants, nor be
directed towards the main areas of public expenditure.'
It acknowledges that there is increasing difficulty in deciding what welfare
activities are normal and proper candidates for public expenditure, as the
government tries to develop a mixed economy of care; but, it says, public
bodies should be excluded from direct benefit.
'It should be made clear that state schools, National Health Service
institutions, local authority social services and other public bodies cannot
apply for lottery support.'
Another common theme in the reports is that lottery proceeds should be
available to the widest range of not-for-profit and voluntary organisations,
and not restricted to registered charities.
Both the 1988 Local Government Act and the new 1992 Charities Act contain
broad definitions of institutions which - although not necessarily
registered charities - are established for philanthropic purposes; the
voluntary sector wants these definitions applied.
Whatever distribution system the government sets up, the question of
deciding which charitable causes should benefit from lottery grants will be
a complex and potentially controversial one. The ACF report says that, while
dividing the available money thinly between all 170,000 registered charities
and a similar number of other voluntary groups might appear fair, it would
involve charities receiving support irrespective of the merit of their work.
'Exercising some discretion in allocating the proceeds is essential to make
a more effective contribution to social welfare. Rather than allocating
money indiscriminately, grants must be awarded on merit, with an application
process providing the basis for initial comparison.'
Both reports argue that a proportion of the lottery proceeds should be used
to benefit low income groups. And, says the ACF, the lottery should provide
an opportunity to redress existing imbalances in the distribution of
charitable money by concentrating some resources on programmes that are
unpopular in conventional fund-raising terms.
Experience gleaned from state lotteries abroad and from UK appeals like
Telethon, it says, suggests that this would be unlikely to arouse public
resistance so long as the lottery funded more 'appealing' and 'photogenic'
causes as well. Indeed, adds the report, 'in many cases it is remarkable how
little interest is shown in the distribution of publicly-raised funds.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
