<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / Survey of Charity Fund Investment (7): Accounting for change
is only the start - Andrew Jack notes that new regulations reflect more
rigorous attidudes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ACCOUNTANTS will be in the ascendancy over the next few months in many
British charities, as a result of tough new legislation and a more vigorous
attitude from regulators.
Detailed regulations in the wake of the 1992 Charities Act, new voluntary
accounting rules for charities on which they may in part be based, and the
sharpening claws of the Charity Commission, will all soon make their
presence felt.
The 1992 Charities Act is the most fundamental. It has brought about even
more sweeping change than the most significant previous Charities Act, in
1960.
By next summer, the Home Office is expected to release a series of detailed
regulations; these are expected to apply from September 1 next year. At
present there is still some uncertainty over their content. But the
principal ones, concerning financial reporting, accounting and auditing,
are:
Accounting records: Proper accounting records must be kept for up to six
years. These must show day-to-day entries of all money spent and received; a
record of assets and liabilities; and other information sufficient to
explain all the charity's transactions, to show its financial position
accurately and enable trustees to ensure that it complies with regulations.
Annual accounts: There will be detailed guidelines on the form and content,
methods and principles, supplementary information in notes to the accounts,
determination of accounting periods and income thresholds.
Annual audit and examination: Accounts of charities with gross income or
expenditure above Pounds 100,000 in the current or previous two years will
require an annual audit from a charity auditor; those below this threshold
but above Pounds 1,000 have the alternative option of an annual audit from
an independent person believed by the trustees to have suitable ability and
practical experience.
Annual report: Within 10 months of the financial year-end, charities will
have to file with the Charity Commissioners, giving a report on the year's
activities and information on the charity and its trustees and officers. The
file must include the audit report on the accounts.
Access to accounts: The charity trustees must provide anyone who asks with a
copy of the latest audited accounts within two months of the request, on
payment of a reasonable copying fee.
These requirements are in addition to existing obligations for charities
which are incorporated and already comply with the requirements of the
Companies Act.
They do not all apply to certain 'excepted' charities subject to other
supervisory requirements; neither do they apply to 'exempt' charities, (such
as those with income of up to Pounds 1,000, no permanent endowment and no
use or occupation of land).
There is general agreement that the quality of financial reporting among
charities has improved considerably. Many larger ones already comply with
the new requirements of the Act, including the employment of an external
auditor.
The quality of financial reporting in smaller charities is far more
variable.
The judges in last month's charity annual report and accounts award warned
that many submissions still made elementary mistakes, such as not including
the accounts with the annual report, or failing to sign and date the balance
sheet.
With the introduction of the new regulations, charities face a double
pincer. The government's willingness to tackle charities with important
legislation has been mirrored by its decision to grant more money to the
Charity Commission.
That has allowed the regulatory body to begin computerising charity
accounts, and may have helped it towards an active role in financial
reporting and enforcing greater accountability from charities.
For example, the commission has pledged that 80 per cent of its list of
principal charities will have lodged their accounts by 1994. In 1989, only
11 per cent of the principal charities registered with the commission lodged
accounts.
By last year it had risen considerably - but it was still only 46 per cent
of the registered 135,000.
The commission has also taken a more significant role in new guidelines on
financial reporting.
SORP 2, the statement of recommended practice first issued in 1988, is being
up-dated. But while the original was driven by the Accounting Standards
Committee, the commission is taking the lead with the new version.
SORP 2 remains voluntary. But it is important, because many larger charities
feel obliged to comply with its guidelines, and because it may form the
basis of the detailed Home Office regulations on the contents of annual
reports and accounts next year.
Pressure from outsiders has called for amendments which would provide
greater information on, say, charities' sources of income; expenditure by
areas of activity; details of costs; valuation of assets; and consolidation
of subsidiaries.
Many charities have traditionally shown reluctance to provide a good deal of
financial information which may easily be misinterpreted. But with wider
realisation of the privileges they receive and the significance of their
assets, they are now being called much more vigorously to account.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
