<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / Survey of Charity Fund Investment (4): Charitable belts
tighten - Voluntary groups face reductions in local authority support
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LOCAL VOLUNTARY groups, many already badly hit by cuts in support from local
authorities in recent years, fear that 1993-94 will be even more difficult.
Local authority budgets are going to be under severe strain as a result of
government efforts to contain public expenditure; the National Council for
Voluntary Organisations expects this to lead to further reductions in the
support councils give to the voluntary sector. It believes there will be
particular problems for organisations providing personal social services,
those relying on inner city grants and voluntary sector training providers.
NCVO officials have protested to Mr Michael Howard, the UK environment
secretary, at proposed reductions in planned Urban Programme funding from
Pounds 231m to Pounds 176m in 1993-94. 'Voluntary organisations are major
recipients of Urban Programme funding,' says Mr Simon Hebditch, NCVO
assistant director. 'It is another cruel blow to voluntary organisations
working in areas of high unemployment and social deprivation.'
Job creation, training, welfare, housing, advice, recreation, environmental
and education projects are all likely to suffer, says Mr Hebditch.
Even before the autumn statement, many local authorities had begun imposing
cuts in voluntary sector funding, freezing budgets at last year's levels or
refusing to accept any new applications for finance.
The overwhelming extent to which local organisations depend on public sector
financial support is shown in the first-ever analysis of sources of
voluntary sector funding in the capital carried out for the London Boroughs
Grants Unit, which awards local authority grants.
Although many corporate donors could not specify what proportion of their
national programmes went to London, the research concluded that private
sector support amounted to only around Pounds 3m in 1991-92 - compared with
Pounds 264m from local and central government, health authorities and
grant-making trusts.
London has some 30,000 voluntary groups providing a striking array of
services. But just over half the total funding was devoted to health and
welfare services and a further 20 per cent to education and training. Almost
all the rest went to organisations involved in housing, the arts, recreation
and the environment.
A Pounds 5m office, conference and resource centre for voluntary groups in
London is planned in the former Jones Brothers department store in Holloway
Road, Islington.
The venture is a partnership between the London Voluntary Service Council
and the City Parochial Foundation, one of the largest grant-making trusts in
the capital.
It is intended that the centre, which could open next year, will provide a
library, information service, exhibition space, conference hall and catering
and creche facilities as well as more than 16,000 square feet of office
space. Some low cost accommodation will be reserved for new voluntary groups
seeking to establish themselves.
Workers in London's voluntary sector are enthusiastic about the scheme,
particularly as it comes at a time of repeated cuts in resources. Mr Tim
Cook, clerk to the City Parochial Foundation, says it would put 'something
in place that will help hundreds of groups for years to come.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 33
</PAGE>
</DOC>
