<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / Survey of Charity Fund Investment (5): Enlightened self
interest - Alan Pike reviews corporate community help
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MEASURED in financial terms alone, corporate support for voluntary
organisations remains a small drop in a large, deep ocean.
The median cash donation from the corporate sector in 1991-1992 was Pounds
152,000. During the same year Oxfam raised Pounds 17m from its charity shops
alone.
The latest Charities Aid Foundation survey shows that in 1991-1992, 213 of
Britain's leading companies gave assistance worth Pounds 206m to charities
and voluntary organisations - 41 per cent of it cash, the remainder in the
form of sponsorship, secondment of staff, use of premises and other kinds of
help. Although the support was important and in some cases vital to the
recipients, it was modest in the context of the total income of all
registered charities - more than Pounds 16bn in 1990.
Corporate support for voluntary organisations is, however, one of the most
sought-after types of assistance because it cannot be measured in financial
terms alone.
It offers voluntary organisations business contacts, opportunities for
partnership, access to specialised skills and potential for the professional
promotion of activities. Sponsoring companies can benefit not only from
improving their image among customers, employees and the wider community,
but by building community activities into staff development programmes.
Last year 48 companies gave more than Pounds 1m in cash and other forms of
support to the voluntary sector. British Telecom headed the list: its total
support came to Pounds 14.49m.
Mr Iain Vallance, BT's chairman, said in a lecture last month that the
company believed community activities should be undertaken for BT's benefit
as well as that of the community. In the company's view there were clear
advantages in corporate community activity, flowing from the fact that its
business depended very considerably on the health of the community. 'If that
health is adversely affected by deprivation, crime, vandalism, racial
tension, inner-city decay, homelessness or pollution, so too is our own
business health. Our opportunities are reduced, our problems increase, our
costs rise.'
The company wanted to be seen as one with a genuine concern for the health
of the community, but platitudes and donations were not enough to achieve
this. It required the involvement of staff. 'Community involvement provides
an opportunity for people in BT to widen their horizons, to see beyond their
jobs, and to recognise the importance of the community upon which we depend
as a company.'
It would once have seemed a trifle vulgar for companies to admit that
self-interest motivated their support for charity. Today, such attitudes are
positively encouraged by enthusiasts for corporate community involvement.
Companies are more likely to take community activities seriously -
increasing the benefit for the community - if they see them in business
rather than philanthropic terms.
Many companies are establishing professional community affairs departments
and turning their voluntary sector involvement into a mainstream business
function. One consequence of this is a growing tendency to support
activities which have a logical association with the company's own business
activities.
Fears are expressed in the voluntary sector that this approach to corporate
sponsorship leads to companies restricting support to popular causes with an
attractive public relations image. This need not be so, as the Sedgwick
Group, insurance and reinsurance brokers, is demonstrating with a policy of
deliberately including within its community programme unpopular causes that
often find it difficult to attract sponsors.
These include organisations working with Aids victims, ex-offenders and the
homeless. The company's staff run a job club in Norwich prison, helping
inmates with the difficult task of seeking employment when they are
released.
Victoria Secretan, Sedgwick's community programmes manager, says that
less-mainstream voluntary sector programmes can still be linked to corporate
objectives.
The insurance sector's approach to Aids raises controversial questions, and
she says that involvement with Aids care has given the company a more
sensitive understanding of the issues involved. As part of its work with
ex-offenders Sedgwick has, in conjunction with the Apex Trust, Business in
the Community and Lloyd's underwriters, developed the Apex Bond - a fidelity
bonding system to help overcome one of the barriers facing employers in the
recruitment of people released from prison.
A survey of business and voluntary sector leaders carried out by KPMG
Management Consulting as part of this year's tenth anniversary celebrations
of Business in the Community - which encourages corporate community activity
 -found that, while 90 per cent of respondents believed the idea of
community involvement made business sense, 56 per cent found it harder to
identify benefits in the case of particular projects.
Lack of clear knowledge of the business case among business leaders was the
most frequently cited obstacle to corporate community involvement, and there
were calls for efforts to measure the effectiveness of projects in, for
example, reducing unemployment and raising socio-economic standards.
A case study of corporate social responsibility, produced for the Chartered
Institute of Bankers by Professor Kevan Scholes and a team from Sheffield
University, says the argument in favour of an active community policy can be
summed up in terms of good business. 'There is no real alternative, and a
positive social responsibility policy may be seen as enlightened
self-interest.'
The case against, says the report, is that 'pursuing active social
responsibility policies puts burdens on both business and society without
producing the intended effect of social improvement.'
The study examines National Westminster Bank, Britain's biggest corporate
supporter of the voluntary sector until BT overtook it last year. Market
research, says the report, showed 'strong staff support' - up to 98 per cent
 -for the bank's approach to community-related projects, with employees
seeking further progress on local initiatives. NatWest has recently
re-focused its community programme to reflect its business priorities, and
the report provides some evidence to support this approach. NatWest
undertook a series of inner city projects after the riots of the early
1980s; the report says there were marked variations in the success of these.
'The projects which succeeded best were those which related to the bank's
own business interests, such as training and technology, whereas those which
were least successful were those which were furthest away from business
interests, such as a day centre for the unemployed in Leeds. The latter was
treated locally with suspicion and cynicism. There was also a belief that
this project addressed symptoms rather than causes.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 33
</PAGE>
