<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / Survey of Charity Fund Investment (3): New eyes on the City
 -Fund management has the potential to be big business
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MANAGING funds for charities suddenly showed the potential to be a big
business this year.
City fund managers, anxious to find a new source of funds, are offering
radically improved packages for charities, while the charities themselves,
in some cases jolted into action by divestment from the Official Custodian
for Charities, are looking at the City with new eyes.
But fund managers are keeping a sense of proportion. Estimates of the total
charities market vary, but it is unquestionably tiny compared with the money
invested in segregated pension funds.
The annual survey of the top 400 grant-making trusts by the Charities Aid
Foundation shows that these bodies control assets of about Pounds 7bn. Total
investment in charity fund managers stands at about Pounds 12bn, and total
long-term investments controlled by the charity sector account, according to
Mr John Harrison, charities director of Lazard Investors, for about Pounds
15bn.
By contrast, pension fund money accounts for about Pounds 300bn. Hymans
Robertson, the consulting actuaries, calculates that Mercury Asset
Management, the biggest manager of segregated pension funds, has Pounds
39.617bn total funds under management. Of this, charities account for only
Pounds 978m.
Part of the problem in expanding the funds under management is that
charities' needs vary much more than those of pension funds. Some are
endowed foundations which make grants. These will normally try to make
grants out of investment income, leaving the capital to grow.
This presents a fund management task wholly different from a fund-raising
charity, which has an irregular stream of income, used to finance on-going
commitments.
Furthermore, certain charities will want their investments constrained by
ethical or political criteria, requiring careful monitoring.
The fund management needed also varies according to the size of a charity. A
large endowed fund, with Pounds 1m or more to invest, probably needs a
segregated fund of directly held securities. The small charities which will
soon divest from the official custodian typically have large holdings of war
loan, or other low-yielding investments, and might be best served by
choosing a pooled investment vehicle, or 'common investment fund.' These
work in the same way as unit trusts, but with the significant advantage that
dividends can be reinvested gross.
Divestment has opened up considerable opportunities for these products as
the official custodian currently arranges for charities to receive their
income gross, but in future charities will need to go through the expensive
administrative hassle of paying tax and then reclaiming it. Common
investment funds would solve this problem.
The market is dominated by the Charities Official Investment Fund, COIF,
which is managed by Church, Charity and Local Authority Fund Managers
(CCLA). Other players include the Charities Aid Foundation, whose funds are
managed by Cazenove, and M&amp;G, a dominant force in the unit trust market.
Recent entrants include large fund managers such as Mercury, Schroders and
Fleming.
The potential influx of money from smaller charities should help to expand
the sector. But at the other end, the Wellcome Trust this year made the
biggest single injection of charitable funds, following the flotation of
part of its holding in Wellcome plc.
Wellcome placed Pounds 2.75bn of new funds with eight City managers
following an extensive 'beauty parade' of 237 applicants. Companies which
did not win a slice of Wellcome's money included Mercury - and James Capel
and Morgan Grenfell, which were both existing managers for the charity. The
winners included Baillie Gifford and Newton, both relatively small fund
managers. Hambros Bank will manage Wellcome's gilt portfolio, while some of
the UK's biggest money managers made up the rest of the list: Fleming,
Gartmore, Henderson, Phillips &amp; Drew, and Schroder.
The sector has also had to adjust to a possible change in the rules
governing the assets in which charities can invest. The Charities Act gave
the home secretary the power to relax the constraints placed on managers by
the Trustee Investment Act 1961. At present this requires a large proportion
of investments to be held in gilts and other fixed-interest securities.
No changes have yet been announced, and it is ironic that this extra freedom
could be introduced just as bonds have come back into favour. For example,
Mr John Thornton, of Glasgow-based fund managers Murray Johnstone, believes
that few charities will take advantage of the extra opportunities, both
because the need for income is important, and because it would be imprudent
to have a fund skewed too far towards equities.
Mr Martyn Bensley, charity fund director at Robert Fleming, agrees that
charity portfolios will typically have a higher element in bonds than other
funds, and will also reduce overseas exposure because of exchange rate
risks.
But the business of charities management is subtle. While many fund managers
have set up specialist teams for charity management, some companies with
pension fund expertise ask their managers to work on both pensions and
charities. This has some attractions as both investments are essentially
long-term, risk-averse, and in a tax-free environment.
Schroders deliberately asks its charity managers also to work on segregated
pension funds, and retains a heavy emphasis on equities, which it says is
necessary to protect capital and increase revenue over the long term.
Others adopt a different approach. According to Kleinwort Benson, linking
pension fund and charity investment is a mistake because charity trustees
think in terms of total returns, while charities tend to have a much more
precise requirement for income.
Mr Mark Summers, senior consultant with James Capel, points out that
charitable trustees are usually in position because they have a specific
interest or skill in the area concerned; by and large they are financially
naive.
'They are very often of a crusading turn of mind, which drives the desire
for maximum distributable revenue. Charity trustees as a body are therefore
much more akin to private clients than they are to institutional clients.'
Also, charitable trustees now seem to have a much wider choice than the
average private client.
