<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / International Capital Markets: Asia-Pacific sees capital
shortfall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CAPITAL markets in the Asia-Pacific region are largely underdeveloped,
volatile and ill-suited to financing the likely demands for capital in the
region in the years ahead.
These are the findings of a survey of more than 500 capital markets experts
in the Far East, Europe and the US, undertaken by Arthur Andersen, the
accounting and consulting group.
Despite high domestic savings rates in most of the countries in the region,
nearly 70 per cent of those surveyed expect a capital shortage in the region
later in the decade. Extensive development of Asian capital markets will be
needed to avoid such a problem, the study concludes.
Respondents to the survey, who included capital markets practitioners,
government officials and academics, pointed to the volatile nature of
securities markets in the region as a cause of concern. The problems are
exacerbated by the partial withdrawal by Japanese banks, which in the 1980s
had provided large volumes of cheap capital to borrowers in some other Asian
countries.
The study found:
The equity markets are expected to remain the dominant capital markets in
the region, due to the high economic growth rates expected in the years
ahead. The 'boom-and-bust' cycle in Japan and, to a lesser extent, South
Korea, Taiwan, Indonesia and Thailand, will change as investors look more at
fundamental value and as institutional investment develops, Andersen
concludes. The result is likely to be a big increase in the demand for asset
management.
UK fund managers, through their historical connections with Hong Kong, have
been the fastest to develop business in the region, but investors from
elsewhere in Europe, and eventually the US, will also become important
investors.
Corporate bond markets remain underdeveloped, with the exception of
Australia and the efforts being made to open up the market in Malaysia. The
demand for stable long-term funds is likely to lead to greater use of
fixed-income finance. Undeveloped government bond markets make the growth of
corporate bond markets more difficult. In some countries, such as Taiwan,
government borrowing plans are so great they are likely to squeeze private
sector borrowers out of the markets.
Asia/Pacific Capital Markets, Economist Intelligence Unit. Pounds 195.
</TEXT>
