<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / International Capital Markets: Finland to inject further
FM15bn into bank sector
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TRACY CORRIGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Finnish government plans to inject a further FM15bn (Dollars 3bn) of
capital into the ailing Finnish banking sector next year, on top of the
FM28bn rescue package already committed.
Mr Sixten Korkman, director general of the Finnish Ministry of Finance, said
the estimate was 'on the safe side', so that further injections would not be
needed in the future.
The support package, set up in March, consists of FM8bn in the form of
preferred stock and FM20bn in the form of a guarantee fund. The package is
designed to ward off the threat of a credit crunch and prevent any bank
collapses.
Finnish banks experienced losses of around FM20bn this year due to the high
level of corporate loan defaults.
But the Finnish prime minister, Mr Esko Aho, said the structural changes
required to strengthen the position of Finland's banks were underway, citing
Skopbank's 30 per cent reduction in staffing levels and the takeover of
STS-Bank by Kansallis-Osake-Pankki, the country's largest bank.
'The ability of the Finnish banking sector to rebound from its current
difficulties is largely dependent on the country's economic recovery,' said
Mr John Gibling, an analyst at Standard &amp; Poor's, the US rating agency.
Analysts warned the scope for further potential problems is hard to predict,
since it is not known how many small and medium-sized Finnish companies are
still on the brink of collapse.
However, after declines of 2 per cent this year and 6 per cent last year,
the government forecast of 2 per cent economic growth next year is described
as realistic.
'Such a bounce from a very low base is certainly possible,' said Mr David
Longmuir at James Capel. 'But it will be up to the export industry, because
with unemployment running at 16 per cent consumers are very cautious.'
The need to inject further capital into the banking system, coupled with the
financial strain of high unemployment, will hold the government's funding
requirement at a high level next year. The borrowing programme, split
between the international and domestic bond markets, will total close to
FM60bn, according to Mr Korkman. But bond traders are not convinced that the
government will be able to raise half the programme domestically, due to
foreign investors' aversion to the domestic market after suffering two
currency devaluations in little over a year.
The level of borrowing is expected to diminish in 1994, assuming next year's
growth target is met.
Mr Aho also reiterated his government's commitment to re-linking the Finnish
markka to other European currencies, following the currency's devaluation in
September.
Moody's, US rating agency, has lowered the ratings of Postipankki's FM1.7bn
of debt to A1 from Aa2. The downgrade applies only to debt issued after
1988, since earlier issues benefit from a guarantee from the Republic of
Finland. Debt issued after that date benefit from a government guarantee
fund but 'the amount of support available is limited,' according to Moody's.
</TEXT>
