FT  10 DEC 92 / International Company News: Premier Group earnings up 23%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP GAWITH
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JOHANNESBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PREMIER GROUP, South Africa's second-largest foods group, has increased
six-month earnings and stepped up its dividend.
Net attributable earnings for the half-year rose 23 per cent to R89.5m
(Dollars 30m) compared to the first half of 1991, and the dividend is going
up by 13 per cent to 36 cents a share.
Turnover increased by 21 per cent to R5.4bn from the restated figure of
R4.5bn in 1991, but Mr Peter Wrighton, chairman, said the performances were
not strictly comparable as the results of the Metro Cash and Carry
acquisition in the previous period covered only four months'trading.
Mr Wrighton described the results as 'most pleasing'. This is shown by
tighter margins, with trading profit only 9 per cent higher at R213m,
against R195m.
The group benefited considerably, however, from lower debt and lower
interest rates - total borrowings fell to R280m from R650m - reflected in
net interest paid declining to R17.7m from R39.4m.
Mr Wrighton said that while most divisions had performed satisfactorily,
certain sectors had suffered from poor trading conditions and reduced
consumer spending. In terms of trading profit, roughly 45 per cent of
Premier's earnings come from food, 28 per cent from pharmaceutical
operations, 12 per cent from wholesaling and 15 per cent from retailing.
The market was anticipating good results, with the share having risen by
more than 20 per cent during the past month. Premier is regarded as a good
defensive stock, which benefits during a recession from its focus on basic
foods and pharmaceuticals.
</TEXT>
