<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / International Company News: IBM shares fall sharply on
speculation over cost cuts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
INTERNATIONAL Business Machines' share price dropped sharply yesterday and
the company's debt rating came into question amid broad speculation that the
large computer group may announce a new round of consolidation and up to
30,000 job cuts as early as next week.
Wall Street analysts said that IBM was expected to hold an emergency meeting
of its board of directors next week to consider a range of cost-cutting
proposals.
Some analysts predicted that these might include IBM's first involuntary
redundancies and the closure of several facilities.
There was rising concern that charges resulting from such cuts could force
IBM to cut its dividend.
'We expect IBM to conclude a dismal 1992 with sizeable further charges,'
said Mr Daniel Mandresh of Merrill Lynch.
'The charge is going to be substantial enough and involve enough people so
that they will not be able to fund the dividend out of cash flow next year,'
said Mr John Jones of Salomon Brothers.
Mr Mandresh also said that IBM may accelerate its plans to separate its
operations into autonomous business units. The strong performance of IBM's
mid-range computer, computer workstation, service and software businesses
were being masked by deteriorating sales of the company's mainframe
computers, Mr Mandresh said.
'It appears to us that IBM's board must find a way to accelerate the process
by which shareholders can focus in on crisply presented results of the
growth segments of the company. We expect sweeping changes at IBM to be
announced shortly and we believe that if possible IBM will introduce changes
in equity ownership,' Mr Mandresh said.
Standard and Poor's, the credit rating agency, said that it was considering
downgrading IBM's debt from its current triple-A rating. About Dollars 9.6bn
of debt is affected.
'The rating action reflects increased uncertainty about the company's
ability to restore performance to levels consistent with a Triple-A rating,'
S&amp;P said.
Previously, S&amp;P indicated that fourth-quarter results and prospects for 1993
would be critical to maintaining the triple-A rating.
'Reports of further write-offs represent an additional concern,' the rating
agency said.
IBM declined to make any comment.
On Wall Street, IBM's shares closed at Dollars 62 5/8 down Dollars 2 3/4 .
</TEXT>
