<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / International Company News: General Dynamics shows nothing
in the portfolio is sacred - Martin Dickson analyses the Dollars 1.525bn
sale of the tactical military business that consolidates Lockheed in this
segment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GENERAL Dynamics, the second-largest US defence contractor, should perhaps
be renamed the Incredible Shrinking Company.
For the announcement yesterday that it intends to sell its tactical military
aircraft business to Lockheed for Dollars 1.525bn in cash is the most
remarkable move yet in a 14-month-long contraction of the company through a
programme of asset sales.
Businesses already sold off include Cessna, the light aircraft manufacturer
(to Textron) and its missiles operations (to Hughes Aircraft) but
yesterday's deal is in an entirely different category, since the aircraft
operations are widely regarded as the company's crown jewel.
The Lockheed deal therefore suggests that nothing in the General Dynamics
portfolio of businesses is now sacred. It is conceivable that it could
shrink to a small rump, holding a lot of cash to be distributed to
shareholders.
This policy of controlled liquidation represents the most dramatic move by a
US defence contractor to cope with the end of the Cold War and the
consequent cuts in Pentagon spending, which is forcing the US military
business into a series of mergers.
Only last month General Electric said it planned to sell its aerospace
division to Martin Marietta for Dollars 3bn.
Mr Jerry Cantwell, an analyst at Wertheim Schroder, thinks that these two
big deals are likely to 'break the jam of defence industry transactions
waiting in the wings'.
The deal also represents a significant consolidation of US military aircraft
capability in the hands of Lockheed, one of the financially and
technologically strongest businesses in the sector.
General Dynamics' tactical military aircraft business, based in Fort Worth
Texas, will have 1992 sales of about Dollars 3bn and employs some 20,000
people worldwide. Its main product is the F-16 fighter.
It is also a member of the three-company team, led by Lockheed and including
Boeing, which last year won a Dollars 9.5bn contract with the US Air Force
to develop the F-22, a new generation of radar-dodging fighters.
The F-22 is supposed to take the place of the F-15 Eagle, the air force's
primary, but ageing fighter, and could be worth tens of billions of dollars
in sales to the contractors over the next 20 years, though rising costs
could eventually pose a threat to the aircraft from Congress. Mr William
Anders, the chairman of General Dynamics, has noted the programme 'could
ultimately become unaffordable because of the growing overheads and
fixed-cost burden' carried by the contractors.
Lockheed, which will now account for two thirds of the F-22 programme,
should be able to reduce these cost overheads, though Mr Daniel Tellep, its
chairman, gave no indication yesterday of how this might be achieved.
Mr Tellep did, however, say that Lockheed hoped to use the F-16's
international sales network to lift its own limited foreign aircraft sales.
Production of the F-16 is well past its 1980s peak, with the Fort Worth
plant building some two dozen this year in a factory designed for annual
output of 256 aircraft.
As US demand has diminished, the Bush administration has gone out of its way
to bolster production at the plant by approving the sale of 150 of the
fighters to Taiwan and a Dollars 1.85bn upgrade of aircraft serving with
four European countries. Lockheed said yesterday that the Fort Worth
division would retain its management and workforce.
Lockheed's aircraft group - with products ranging from the C-130 transport
to the F-117 stealth fighter, provides about a quarter of the group's
revenues.
Analysts had argued that it would benefit from greater mass in this area and
the General Dynamics deal would provide that, creating a Dollars 6.5bn
military aircraft business ranking first in the industry.
The deal, will, however, make it harder for Lockheed to meet its long-term
goal of a 60-40 mix between its defence and non-defence businesses, compared
to the current 70-30 ratio.
Some strategists argue there is little point in defence contractors trying
to diversify their way into civilian business to overcome the shrinking
defence budget, since their record in other areas is so poor. Far better to
bunker down and concentrate on running their core military businesses more
efficiently.
This argument has been embraced strongly by Mr Anders, who this year
announced plans to sell off non-defence businesses and concentrate on four
areas, which might be built up by acquisitions - tactical military aircraft;
armoured vehicles; nuclear submarines and space launch systems.
What has surprised Wall Street is Mr Anders's willingness to sell off one of
these supposedly core operations.
However, Mr Anders has complained that his efforts to buy businesses have
been frustrated by the reluctance of other defence contractors to sell off
sub-critical businesses. He warned that he would be willing to dispose of an
operation if this was the best way of keeping its franchise viable.
The Lockheed deal reflects this, and may eventually lead to another share
buy-back.
</TEXT>
