FT  10 DEC 92 / International Company News: Elf chairman sees recovery in
net profits next year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ELF AQUITAINE, the French oil group, expects net profits to recover next
year after falling by around 35 per cent in 1992, said Mr Loik Le
Floch-Prigent, chairman.
He attributed the likely fall, from a FFr9.8bn (Dollars 1.81bn) net profit
in 1991, to the decline in the dollar's value, the fall in oil prices and
factors linked to the economic slowdown. These included 'very bad' refining
margins, 'considerable' overcapacity in the petrochemical industry, a
collapse in French demand for diesel and petrol during last summer's truck
strike, and a delay in fertiliser orders caused by farmers' fears of the
impact of European Community agricultural policy reforms.
Margins for all of Elf's products had been hit in the UK, Italy and Spain
because of the decline in their currencies against the franc.
Mr Le Floch-Prigent pointed out, however, that Elf's profits fall would be
less serious than that likely from some competitors. Oil production had
increased and distribution of special oil products and speciality chemicals
had done well. Elf Sanofi, the group's pharmaceutical subsidiary, would also
have a strong year, helped by its alliance with Sterling Drug of the US.
Elf Aquitaine planned to trim investments during the downturn but would
stick to its basic strategy, which has been to keep a rough balance between
upstream and downstream operations, with a slight bias towards production,
the group's traditional domain. Mr Le Floch-Prigent expected oil prices to
recover to around Dollars 20 per barrel next year, from Dollars 18.84
currently.
