<PROFILE>_AN-CLJCGAEQFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921210
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / UK Company News: Supply side helps Manweb to Pounds 37m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN IMPROVED performance from its supply business helped Manweb, the
electricity company supplying Merseyside, west Cheshire and North Wales, to
raise first-half pre-tax profits by 35 per cent from Pounds 27.5m to Pounds
37.1m.
Sales rose 9 per cent to Pounds 409m (Pounds 375m) and the interim dividend
is lifted by 12 per cent to 6.1p (5.45p).
Separately, Mr John Roberts, chief executive, indicated support for the idea
that the liberalisation of the electricity supply market should be delayed
if companies were to be asked to buy more coal-fired electricity.
He also joined other regional electricity companies in expressing scepticism
about the possibility of agreeing to a contract, covering either one or five
years, with generators prior to the publication of the government's energy
white paper.
In the half-year to September 30 supply losses were reduced from Pounds
13.8m to Pounds 2.7m. The company cited management of purchase costs as the
main factor, helped by a 15 per cent unit volume improvement partly from
securing contracts in the competitive market.
Distribution volumes increased by about 1 per cent, with industrial and
commercial growth offsetting a 1 per cent reduction to the domestic sector.
However, profits from this source fell to Pounds 40.6m (Pounds 44.4m),
affected by a freeze in prices.
Improved margins on steady sales enabled retailing to turn in a Pounds
200,000 operating profit, against a Pounds 200,000 loss previously.
In contracting, however, losses increased from Pounds 100,000 to Pounds
600,000, resulting from a 5 per cent fall in sales, blamed on the recession,
and the non-recurring costs of establishing a contracting subsidiary from
August.
Mr Roberts said the subsidiary was now trading at breakeven and profits were
expected from next year.
Pre-tax profits were reduced by provisions of Pounds 4m (Pounds 2.5m) to
tackle staff reductions. Mr Roberts said he did not expect provisions to
increase at the year end.
COMMENT
One of the clouds hanging over other regional electricity companies will
almost certainly lift today when the regulator exonerates them of blame in
the 'dash for gas,' and that may affect some of the sentiment surrounding
Manweb. As the one rec which is not involved in a gas-fired power station
its shares have benefited in recent months. Nonetheless, Manweb's place as
one of the star shares of the sector is unlikely to be changed either by
today's announcement or yesterday's results. Distribution volumes are rising
during the recession, even if the higher margin domestic sales are down;
supply business lost last year is returning and retailing is back in profit
when most other suppliers are still suffering losses. Contracting is a blot,
but that is a familiar story and new staff terms are already in place for an
improvement. The shares at 471p, down 2p, have a prospective yield of 5.8
per cent, assuming a 20.5p dividend.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 24
</PAGE>
