<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / UK Company News: Greenalls steady at Pounds 64.4m 'in a
harsh climate'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP RAWSTORNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GREENALLS Group, continuing its transformation from regional brewer to
national retailer and hotelier with a Pounds 108m capital spending
programme, achieved a marginal increase in annual pre-tax profits from
Pounds 64.1m to Pounds 64.4m.
The result - in line with market expectations - showed 'resilience . . . in
response to the harsh economic climate,' said Mr Andrew Thomas, chairman and
chief executive.
He said the Pounds 86m raised from a rights issue in October would enable
further 'careful and cautious' expansion.
Basic earnings per share for the year to September 25, excluding property
profits, rose 7 per cent to 29.6p. A final dividend of 6.93p raises the
total by 7 per cent to 11.77p.
Group operating profit of Pounds 77.4m was 6 per cent higher on turnover 8.5
per cent ahead at Pounds 529.1m. But the surplus on property disposals
declined from Pounds 10.1m to Pounds 7.21m. There was an extraordinary
charge of Pounds 14.9m relating to the write-down in value of the group's US
hotels.
Pub profits, helped by rigorous cost controls and the acquisition of 39
outlets, increased by 6.1 per cent to Pounds 47.51m. Turnover was 6 per cent
ahead at Pounds 185.9m.
Beer volumes were down 5.2 per cent but food sales increased from 5.8 per
cent to 7.1 per cent of turnover. Investment in upgrading and expanding the
estate, which now stretches from the group's north-west base into the
northern Home Counties, totalled Pounds 30m.
Premier House, the catering inns and restaurants division, achieved profits
growth of 31 per cent to Pounds 8.4m on turnover up from Pounds 39.5m to
Pounds 43m. Spending on development of the outlets for the family market
amounted to Pounds 16m.
Operating profits from UK hotels fell 9 per cent to Pounds 14.2m. Occupancy
rates were maintained at 60 per cent, helped by an improvement in the second
half, but room rates declined 7.6 per cent to Pounds 48. Losses of the US
hotels were reduced from Pounds 700,000 to Pounds 400,000.
Off-licences, with an eight-month contribution from the Blayneys
acquisition, maintained margins at 18 per cent while improving profits from
Pounds 3.3m to Pounds 4.5m. Drinks and services' profits were marginally
lower at Pounds 6.2m (Pounds 6.4m) but rationalisation and an agreement with
Del Monte for the production and distribution of fruit-based soft drinks
should improve profitability this year.
COMMENT
Greenalls has so far shown a shrewd eye for a bargain, picking up some good
hotel and pub assets from the receiver as it expands its operations
nationally. That provides a measure of reassurance for the market as it
continues its heavy spending programme with a budgeted Pounds 88m this year.
The Pounds 86m rights issue has strengthened the balance sheet, reducing
gearing from 27 per cent to 15 per cent. Internal cash flow should cover the
maintenance of existing businesses, leaving the group with about Pounds 100m
to spend on further acquisitions over the next three years without exceeding
its self-imposed gearing ceiling of 30 per cent. Analysts expect pre-tax
profits of about Pounds 67m this year, putting it on a prospective p/e of
12.6. The stock could be under-valued.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 24
</PAGE>
</DOC>
