<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / UK Company News: Background to the mysterious Mr Fixit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR DIETER BOCK has established a reputation in Germany as an effective, if
mysterious Mr Fixit, with close links to Mr Ignaz Walter, head of the Walter
Bau construction empire.
In his greatest coup to date he played a key role in helping Mr Walter to
promote his company to the second biggest construction group in the country.
He began his real estate investment career in 1974 in Munich. He attracted
considerable attention in 1989 when his Advanta Management, a modest
property-based concern, bought a 10 per cent stake in Philip Holzmann,
Germany's biggest builder. At the end of 1991, he announced Advanta's
takeover of Dywidag, another construction concern, even though it emerged
later that he held only about 25 per cent of the equity, bought from Philip
Holzmann, at the time.
This subsequently finished up in the hands of Walter Bau, which held a
similar stake, and which finally won control of Dywidag in May this year.
Although the deal has yet to receive final clearance from the cartel
authorities in Berlin, Mr Bock, a lawyer, has been offered an option on a 10
per cent stake in Mr Walter's next empire-building project: Walter Holding.
This will encompass all the construction interests of Mr Walter and his
family - Walter Bau, Ed. Zublin, Heilit &amp; Werner, and Dywidag - in a group
due to be floated sometime next year. Total turnover is expected to be about
DM10bn (Pounds 4.1bn) a year.
Another more high-profile adventure brought Advanta a 50 per cent stake in
the Kempinski Hotel chain after the failure of attempts to merge it with the
Meridien business owned by Air France.
The deal was worth an estimated DM300m and again raised questions, still
unanswered, about the source of Mr Bock's finances. According to Advanta's
company reports, it made pre-tax profits of DM63.5m in 1991 on its main
businesses: 'conception, planning and completion of property projects.' Its
net asset at December 31, 1991, were DM200m.
Mr Bock stressed yesterday he was making his investment in Lonrho as a
private shareholder and not through Advanta.
He has a direct 20 per cent personal stake in Advanta, and is reported to
'have influence' over a further 60 per cent held by Dutch-registered
property concerns. The balance is held by BHF bank.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
