<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / UK Company News: Amstrad shareholders reject Sugar's bid for
privatisation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Amstrad shareholders appear to have firmly rejected Mr Alan Sugar's bid to
take the company he founded private again with a 30p-a-share buy-back offer
for the stock he does not already own, writes Paul Taylor.
Although shareholders attending today's Amstrad meetings could still approve
the deal if proxy votes were withdrawn and reversed, Mr Sugar's advisers
conceded that it was now 'technically possible but practically impossible'
for the bid to succeed.
Based on the 13,086 proxy forms received by 2.15pm on Tuesday, 7,827
shareholders or almost 60 per cent were against Mr Sugar's proposed 'scheme
of arrangement'.
Amstrad has 31,000 shareholders and under one test of support Mr Sugar's
proposals needed the backing of at least half those shareholders voting in
person or by proxy to proceed.
Under a second test of support, Mr Sugar also had to win the support of
three quarters - or all but 93.9m - of the 375.6m Amstrad shares he does not
already own. His bid has also failed this test on the basis of the proxies
received.
