<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / UK Company News: Lonrho debt has risen to Pounds 947m -
Reduction in borrowings significant factor behind German deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LONRHO's determination to reduce borrowings was one of the main factors
behind yesterday's deal with Mr Dieter Bock, the German financier.
Shareholders in the international trading group may be perplexed to learn
that net debt has risen to Pounds 947m.
In March they were told at the annual meeting that net debt, which would be
significantly reduced, stood at about Pounds 850m.
Since then the acquisition of a majority stake in Gewog, a German company
which owns 4,300 flats, has inflated the overall debt figure by Pounds 135m.
Lonrho yesterday said debt also increased by Pounds 54m because of exchange
adjustments to foreign currency borrowings and a further Pounds 24m in
respect of UK motor trading operations.
So in spite of more than Pounds 500m of asset sales earlier this year, at
the half year to March 31 net debt had only fallen from Pounds 1.1bn to
Pounds 903m.
It has increased again in spite of two further disposals:
Firsteel Group, a narrow steel strip processor and distributor, was sold to
its management for a price close to its Pounds 21m net asset value.
George Outram, publisher of the Glasgow-based Herald and Evening Times, went
for Pounds 74m to the management, backed by institutions.
However, some analysts believe the net debt is higher than Pounds 947m,
because the Pounds 500m from asset disposals earlier in the year included
Pounds 178m from the sale of a one third stake in the Metropole Hotel chain
to the Libyan Arab Foreign Investment Company.
The group said at the time of the deal in March that the proceeds would be
used to cut the Metropole's borrowings and 'to generate further profits
through developments.'
Earlier in the year Lonrho disposed of its 50 per cent interest in Kuhne and
Nagel, the German freight forwarder, for DM340m (Pounds 140m). It also sold
Scottish and Universal Newspapers for Pounds 45m to Trinity International
Holdings.
Mr Mike Smith, conglomerates analyst at Robert Fleming Securities, said
Lonrho needed a rights issue 'because it has already sold the best
businesses and was clearly not going to make significant inroads into net
debt by relying only on further disposals.'
</TEXT>
