</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COSTAIN, the construction group, is required to pay a Dollars 5m (Pounds
3.2m) compensation fee to Hanson after it cancelled an agreement to sell its
Australian coal-mining business to Peabody, a Hanson subsidiary.
According to a circular to Costain shareholders, the payment is a
termination fee and liquidated damages agreed with Peabody in the event that
sale was not completed. Costain cancelled the agreement to sell the mining
business for Dollars 200m after it received a Dollars 245m offer from Altus
Finance.
The payment is not linked with the legal dispute between Costain and Peabody
concerning abandonment of the deal. Peabody, which began legal action in the
US on November 10 is alleging Costain sought the offer from Altus and
breached its agreement by negotiating with Altus.
On November 16, Costain started proceedings in London against Peabody,
seeking a declaration that it was entitled to negotiate with Altus.
The shareholders' circular also revealed that the company's net debt at
October 30 has increased from Pounds 172.4m to Pounds 340.4m since the end
of 1991.
A substantial part of this increase resulted from refinancing of the group's
share of borrowings of Spitalfields Holdings, the joint venture company
owned by Costain, BICC and London &amp; Edinburgh Trust. This resulted in Pounds
56.1m of borrowings coming onto the group's balance sheet.
