<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / Marines move into Mogadishu: UN aid worker wounded as US
troops take control of Somali capital
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIAN OZANNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOGADISHU
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
US MARINES in desert camouflage and black face paint stormed inland and took
the war-ravaged Somali capital Mogadishu yesterday.
By nightfall more than 1,300 Marines had been set down in the ruined capital
by Hovercraft, amphibious and helicopter landings, and had secured the
airport, port and the looted former US embassy compound. The swift
operation, which marks the start of the biggest foreign military and
humanitarian action ever taken in Africa, went off smoothly with only a few
shots fired and no casualties.
At the airport, Marines in armoured vehicles secured the control tower,
establishing a 24-hour all-weather communications operation for the first
time since civil war erupted two years ago. US Galaxy, Starlifter and
Hercules military transport aircraft streamed in, closely followed by the
first big relief flight for weeks. Shootings and extortion at the airport
had led to the cancellation of flights.
The day was marred, however, when a United Nations aid worker was shot and
wounded on the airport road by gunmen. The UN immediately announced the
suspension of relief flights.
Mogadishu harbour, where aid workers had been beset by robbing and extorting
gunmen, was also secured. Somalis, were stunned by the size and intensity of
the US operation and the constant buzz of Cobra helicopter gunships above
the devastated capital well into the night.
Thousands of the city's residents spent all day perched on sand dunes and
rooftops overlooking the port and airport. In the streets, they sang and
clapped as they surrounded Marines out on patrol and tried to start
conversations in broken English. 'We were the biggest show the folks here
have ever seen,' said Col Fred Peck, the US Marine spokesman. 'We must have
looked like Barnum and Bailey to them.'
In a remarkably honest assessment of the damage inflicted on the country by
the rival ambitions of warlords, Mr Ali Mahdi Mohamed, the self-styled
interim president who controls the north of the city, apologised to his
ruined nation in a radio broadcast. 'Each day we should remind ourselves of
the destruction we have made to our country to serve as a moral and guilty
conscience and to warn ourselves to resolve our differences in negotiations
rather than in killing ourselves.'
A contingent of 180 French foreign legionnaires also landed in Mogadishu and
said they would spend the next 10 days in the capital preparing for the
arrival of a total of 2,100 French troops.
In Kismayo, the vital southern port which has witnessed some of the worst
violence, aid workers were forced to evacuate the city after a night of clan
violence and an attack by gunmen on the Red Cross compound.
In the next phase of the operation, the Marines will head for the town of
Baidoa and secure the 10,000ft runway there to start flying in food.
Marines make first easy inroads, Page 6
</TEXT>
