<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / Congress rejects Gaidar as premier
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
RUSSIAN PRESIDENT Boris Yeltsin suffered his most serious political setback
since coming to power 18 months ago with the rejection by the Congress of
People's Deputies of Mr Yegor Gaidar as his prime minister.
Mr Gaidar narrowly missed confirmation in his post by the Congress - 467
votes to 486 against - but he is likely to remain as acting prime minister
for the immediate future.
Mr Gaidar said after the vote that the government should 'carry on working
calmly'. He, and other senior colleagues, feel it is essential to continue
reforms, especially the privatisation programme, as long as possible.
If Mr Gaidar is reappointed, even in a temporary capacity, the reforms would
continue. They would be moderated, not so much by yesterday's vote as by the
concessions already given to the opposition Civic Union and pledges made on
extra spending.
The vote came on what is expected to be the penultimate day of a Congress
which has showed both its enmity to the consequences of economic reform and
its desire to claw back powers from the presidency to itself.
However, the closeness of the vote and the lack of an alternative prime
ministerial figure from the ranks of the opposition, make it likely that Mr
Yeltsin will today propose Mr Gaidar as acting prime minister once more,
pending the adoption of a law on government which would define the powers
enjoyed by the presidency and the parliament.
Mr Mikhail Mityukov, chairman of the parliament's legislation committee,
said last night that Mr Yeltsin could appoint Mr Gaidar for a period of
three months after a new law on government had come into force.
The president's alternatives are: to propose Mr Gaidar once again, possibly
offering further compromises to attract more votes; to propose another
figure; or to take the step of dissolving a parliament which has shown
itself willing to wound him.
Political opinion last night was firmly on the side of the three-month
appointment option.
Mr Gaidar's closest aide, Mr Vladimir Mau, said: 'The vote confirms Gaidar
as a major political figure. We didn't expect anything like half. No one
else could have got as much.'
Mr Yeltsin suffered some humiliation as a result of having put forward a
compromise deal which was accepted without recompense. The Congress voted to
accept his offer that it be allowed veto rights over four ministers other
than the prime minister (defence, foreign affairs, interior and security)
before it voted against Mr Gaidar - precisely the result the deal was
supposed to prevent.
He and Mr Gaidar have also offered changes in the cabinet and in economic
policy.
