<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / The Lex Column: BAT Industries
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
After Eagle Star's performance in recent years, another Pounds 450m from its
parent could look like more money going up in smoke. But BAT Industries'
decision to prop up its insurance subsidiary has offensive as well as
defensive motivation.
From one viewpoint, the very need to provide such a sum reveals the stark
extent to which Eagle Star's financial strength has been eroded by lingering
recession and the continuing mortgage indemnity crisis. In this regard,
Eagle Star is not alone; capital-raising exercises in recent weeks by the
likes of General Accident and Royal Insurance have been applied to similar
ends. Yet, in boosting the solvency ratio of its general business to more
than 50 per cent, Eagle Star is also positioning itself to compete
aggressively for new business. The marked upswing in the property and motor
insurance sectors since the spring provides the opportunity.
Happily for Eagle Star, its parent company can afford the injection simply
by diverting some of its ample cash flow from tobacco. The operation will
add a mere 3 percentage points to BAT's gearing, taking it to around 58 per
cent. Eagle Star's rivals are less lucky. They can only resort to the equity
market for the scale of funds they may still need. Like the food retailers
last year, the stronger players must be tempted to get in first and
challenge their weaker competitors to follow if they dare.
</TEXT>
