<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / The Lex Column: Tiny's hand unfrozen
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Lonrho's deal with Mr Dieter Bock may be a good one for Mr Tiny Rowland, its
largest shareholder. That can hardly be true for other shareholders,
especially the army of small investors left behind after UK institutions
largely withdrew. Mr Rowland is shedding nearly half his stake at an
outrageous 45 per cent premium to the market. Others, who might have liked
an equal opportunity, are left to sweat it out. Where are the non-executive
directors on Lonrho's board who might have looked after their interests as
the deal was hatched?
By underwriting the rights issue at a premium, Mr Bock could end up with as
much as 19 per cent of Lonrho. The decent thing would be to make an offer
for the rest at the 115p which Mr Rowland is receiving. More likely, his
arrival signals an accelerated breakup of the company, especially after last
night's disposal of VAG. Some of the remaining assets are attractive.
Doubtless Genting would like the hotels and Gencor the South African mining
interests.
With net assets per share of 157p, breakup ought to enhance shareholder
value. But that begs a lot of questions. Net asset value has fallen by
around a quarter over the past year. Some of the cash in the group balance
sheet is effectively locked up in Metropole hotels. Moreover, it is hard to
see how any surplus proceeds could be transferred to shareholders. Lonrho
already has an ACT problem: a higher dividend or even a share buy-back
programme would make that worse. To hold on requires an enormous act of
faith when Mr Bock's own origins are so obscure. More unnerving still, is
that Mr Rowland, who knows all Lonrho's secrets, seems finally to be
thinking of calling it a day.
</TEXT>
