<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / Letter: Not a burdensome inclusion in All-Share Index
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr PETER JONES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Mr Martyn Arbib perhaps overstates his case (Letters, December 7) in
criticising the inclusion of specialist investment trusts in the expansion
of the FT-Actuaries All-Share Index from January 1 1993.
The investment trusts that he named, all specialists in overseas markets,
have a total market value of less than Pounds 250m - well below a tenth of 1
per cent of the value of the All-Share Index. If these shares doubled while
the remaining shares of the All-Share remained in aggregate unchanged, the
effect would be an outperformance of the same amount, that is, less than a
tenth of 1 per cent. Hardly burdensome]
Pursuing Mr Arbib's argument to its ultimate conclusion would, of course,
exclude huge swathes of constituents of the All-Share Index. Would he also
exclude BAT, Guinness, Reuters, BP - because of their heavy overseas
businesses - to name but a handful?
The All-Share Index has been expanded to meet a perceived need of a broad
cross-section of fund managers and investors. The addition of some 150
stocks will expand the market value of the index by some 1 per cent. Its
re-design can never satisfy all - but will, I trust, meet the needs of most.
Peter Jones,
chairman,
FTSE Actuaries UK Index Committee,
Greenwell Montagu Stockbrokers,
7 Devonshire Square,
London EC2M 4HU
</TEXT>
