<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / Letter: Wider relevance of coup defeat in Venezuela
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Dr B S MCBETH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, I could not agree more fully with your leader ('Perilous moment',
December 7) on Venezuela and Peru. The defeat last week of the second
attempted military coup in Venezuela in less than 12 months should be looked
at as a sign of strengthening the democratic basis of government in the
country, and the administration of President Carlos Andre Perez should be
congratulated on insisting that elections for state governorships and over
5,000 other posts at local level be held as scheduled on December 6. This is
of particular significance to the rest of Latin America where the spectre of
authoritarianism may be raising its ugly head once again.
The opposition party, Copei, as expected won the majority of the state
governorships, but the important point is that the country has probably
entered into a new level of political maturity under which change is
undertaken through the ballot box and not by the men in uniform. The current
government of Venezuela faces serious political and economic problems in the
coming months which will lead to further political uncertainty, as any other
government has to tackle during its period in office. However, it should be
obvious that a military solution is not one of the answers.
It is encouraging that in other parts of the region a similar type of
experience is happening with the impeachment process of President Collor
under way in Brazil and elections being forced on President Fujimori in Peru
to reinstate Congress. The region faces grave problems and difficult
political and economic decisions ahead, but it should be clear to the
military from recent events that the toppling of a democratically elected
government only serves to complicate matters and obstruct development.
B S McBeth,
Oxford Consultancy Group,
73 Princes Street,
Oxford OX4 1DE
</TEXT>
