<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / Arts: Looking back - 'A Penny for a Song'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALASTAIR MACAULAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
One of the main English notions about England is that it is brimful of
darling, impractical eccentrics; that the most shattering events of history
have occurred abroad; that England is a safe and charming refuge from the
real world; and that things have been so for centuries - and should continue
so.
So it is in John Whiting's 1951 comedy A Penny for a Song, set in 1804,
during the Napoleonic Wars, and currently revived (in its 1962 revised text)
at the Orange Tree, Richmond. Sir Timothy plans to repulse the invading
French army by impersonating Napoleon and - using French from a textbook -
ordering it to go back home. His sister-in-law Hester prepares to join the
East Anglian Amazon corps. Meanwhile their cricketing neighbour 'Stumper'
Selincourt trains a very amateur home guard. And so on. Everything is very,
very charming.
There are still those who love this kind of pretty treacle; but I am too
conscious of its deliberate unreality to relax to its comedy. A Penny for a
Song wants to evoke the Shallow and Silence scenes in Henry IV Part Two, and
the Dogberry episodes of Much Ado; and it reminds us now of the dafter
flights of Dad's Army. I love an English comic idyll too. Whiting's play,
however, more anodyne and escapist than all these, tries to hug England for
its sillier Englishnesses and to be wistful about it as well.
The giveaway comes in the quaintly stylised language. ('I'll not believe
that this day, this so-called Armageddon, can pass without our being
needed.') Nothing like 1804 parlance, nor much like 1951, this talk apes
Oscar Wilde. Especially the play's do-nothing spectator, Hallam Matthews: 'I
have published three polemical pamphlets on quite uncontroversial subjects.'
But Wilde's delicious sting is here replaced by mere charm. Whiting had not
the force to tease England. He merely wanted to love it, with a laugh and
also a little sigh.
And he came to sense his play's inclination to excessive idyllic escapism.
His 1962 re-write beefs up the role of Edward, the one character in the play
who talks of the value of revolution, the horrors of war and the importance
of social change. I am grateful for every window on the real world that this
character opens. But even Edward has buckets of charm. By the end of the
play, it matters more to us that he and Hester's daughter Dorcas may end up
in true love than that he may pursue his politics.
Every other character in the play is conceived not to be convincingly
lifelike but to be theatrically adorable. Sam Walters's direction emphasises
this. As Hallam Matthews, Michael Elwyn speaks in carefully fluted tones
that chiefly evoke Alan Bennett as a C. of E. vicar. Like David Timson's Sir
Timothy and Auriol Smith's Hester, he projects his own consciousness that he
is playing an English eccentric. And thereby underlines the unreality,
pointlessness and harmlessness of the whole play.
At the Orange Tree, Richmond, until December 19, and from December 29 till
January 30
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 17
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-2932</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CLJCGAC7FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921210
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / Arts: 'Weldon Rising' bares the breast - Theatre
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALASTAIR MACAULAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Replete with bare-breasted lesbian sex, three versions of the same fatal
stabbing, a gay male couple, a transvestite male prostitute and a homocidal
homophobe, here is the best new play I have seen in many months. Its
excellence is not to do with its more sensational features, though they are
necessary to it. This play is exciting because it is well written, unusually
constructed, and (Leavis voice) morally serious. It is also (Macaulay voice)
frequently funny. What makes it serious is that it is all about fear and
responsibility.
Jimmy, who has lived with Natty Weldon for 15 years, is stabbed to death by
a nameless boy in the meat-packing district of New York during a heatwave.
(The temperature is 120 and rising.) Natty is so scared that he runs away
before Jimmy has even died. Three other people, however, observe the whole
murder. They are Marcel, the transvestite, and the two dikes Jaye and Tilly.
This draws them and Natty gradually into a web of quasi-complicity, because
life changes for them all after the murder.
They all have different accounts of the murder and drastically different
descriptions of the murderer. And their accounts change; and Natty, growing
feverish through grief, guilt (over cowardice) and heat, keeps re-telling,
and re-living, his past with Jimmy with different emphasis. The different
versions of the same facts give this play a Rashomon-like quality.
Ultimately, however, the play
The Royal Court, Theatre Upstairs, until December 19 aims to link its
characters in a kind of moral coherence. It ends - too suddenly - in several
kinds of apotheosis. The conclusion is the play's most peculiar and least
satisfying feature, but every bit of it is riveting.
The playwright, Phillis Nagy, is American and gay. I like the fact that she
treats gay sexuality and gay society simply as objective facts, without
preaching any pro- or anti-gay sermons. To say that one wants to see more
work by her is true, but also condescending. Weldon Rising is achievement
enough. (At 75 minutes - no interval - it is, if anything, too short.)
I would like to speak more of the play's moral acuity - but what makes the
Weldon Rising audience most grateful is its precise characterisation,
first-rate dialogue, superb construction and fine acting. The most
noteworthy character, the transvestite Marcel, always talks of himself in
the third person. (Jaye: 'Why do you refer to yourself in the third person?
Marcel: 'Marcel is the third person.') This is entertaining; it also works
ironically in a play about spectators. The play interleaves past and present
powerfully; and Natty, speaking now with hindsight, even interviews Jimmy,
speaking as he did 15 years back - like the wise-after-the-fact
conversations we all have in our heads.
Every praise to the director, Penny Ciniewicz, for this co-production with
the Liverpool Playhouse Studio. And to the cast of six: Simon Gregor
(Natty), Andrew Woodall (Marcel), Melee Hutton (Tilly), Rosie Rowell (Jaye),
Paul Viragh (Jimmy) and Matthew Wait (the killer) all catch perfectly the
mixture of naturalism and irony in the writing. The action is taut, with not
an ounce of waste flesh. Seats in the middle of the rows are recommended.
Make an effort to ensure you arrive early enough to claim them.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 17
</PAGE>
