<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / Management (Marketing and Advertising): Reopening the road
to Rio - Christina Lamb on Brazilian eco-tourism
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTINA LAMB
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Samba dancers, voluptuous girls in dental floss bikinis and football are the
images most people have of Brazil, according to Embratur, the state tourist
authority.
A marketing campaign by the Brazilian government and private sector aims to
change this in a desperate attempt to resuscitate the country's ailing
tourist industry.
Aimed at the travel trade and individual tourists, the focus is to show
Brazil as a paradise for eco-tourists.
The 'Natureland Brazil' campaign involves an advertising blitz and the use
of Brazilian musicians as 'ambassadors'.
It aims to show that Brazil has far more to offer than the picture postcard
resort of Rio which despite its beauty has become a liability because of its
huge crime rate.
The campaign marks a belated realisation of the need to invest money in
marketing to attract tourists. Unlike Mexico and Venezuela, which have
slapped travel posters on London buses and the New York subway, Brazil has
spent nothing.
The result, according to Varig, Brazil's largest airline, is that tourism
has more than halved to 900,000 visitors since 1985.
The Dollars 550,000 (Pounds 360,000) campaign is financed by Embratur, Varig
and American Express Brazil, and aims to double income from tourism to
Dollars 3bn in the next five years.
The campaign began last month with a US tour by Milton Nascimento, one of
Brazil's leading musicians who frequently sings about Indians and the
environment. Each concert starts and ends with a three-minute video showing
the country's environmental highlights.
Amex Brazil and Varig are running a campaign in specialist magazines under
the McCann Erickson-developed slogan: 'Feel the Brazilliance.' In addition
the two companies are sponsoring seminars for travel agents in US gateway
cities.
American Express is also direct mailing to 150,000 of its US cardholders.
The campaign is aimed at US tourists whose numbers have fallen largely
because of crime in Rio.
Joao Luis de Souza, commercial director of Varig, adds: 'What Brazil hasn't
done is to think of tourism as a professional activity to be explored using
management strategies, technology and marketing. It's all been very ad hoc
and now we're paying the price.'
To back up the campaign and make ecotourism viable, Varig is building hotels
and has created direct links from Europe and the US to cities such as
Recife, convenient for the beaches of the north east, or Manaus and Belem
for exploring the Amazon.
Although de Souza estimates that Brazil currently receives only
20,000-30,000 ecotourists a year, he says: 'The world is growing
increasingly conscious of the importance of preserving the environment for
the survival of mankind. It is inevitable that this will increase curiosity
for seeing the environment in its natural form and where better than
Brazil?'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 15
</PAGE>
