<HEADLINE>
FT  10 DEC 92 / Parliament and Politics: Mortgage lenders warn on further
base-rate cuts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHOEBE KING and JOHN GAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BUILDING SOCIETIES are unlikely to be able to pass on the full amount of any
further cuts in base rates because they have to maintain their rates on
savings products, leaders of the mortgage lending industry said yesterday.
Mr Tim Melville-Ross, chairman of the Council of Mortgage Lenders, said that
because interest on long - term investments was now higher than on
short-term savings products, building societies could not lower mortgage
rates much further.
He told the Treasury and Civil Service committee: 'The extent to which we
will be able to reflect further reductions in base rates will be limited.' A
reduction of 1 percentage point was 'just not on'.
The statement came after a call by Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, for
building societies to pass on the whole of recent base-rate cuts to lenders.
Societies say they have to widen margins in order to compensate for mortgage
losses.
Mr Mark Boleat, director general of the Building Societies Association, said
lenders would be wrong to reduce rates and then put them up to restore
profitability.
The association said in written evidence to the committee that the industry
was suffering a net outflow of savings funds this year because of
competition from longer term investments.
Mr Brian Pitman, chief executive of Lloyds Bank, said the bank's overall
margin on domestic lending had fallen over the past 10 years. He said the
scope to raise margins was limited by the lack of demand, and market
competition.
He told MPs it was not bank policy to widen margins and the average
difference between the rate charged and the cost of funding loans had
narrowed about 0.5 per cent in the past year.
The average margin was 2.8 per cent in 1991 compared with about 2.3 per cent
around the middle of this year, he said.
Mr Pitman denied increasing margins on loans to small businesses to support
profits in the recession.
He strongly denied claims that bank charges were tipping companies into
bankruptcy.
'It's not in our interests to push a company into liquidation,' he said,
adding that Lloyds was 'sharing the pain' with its customers.
Mr Pitman also said the worst of the recession appeared to have passed and
signs of recovery were growing.
Sir Bryan Carsberg, director general of fair trading, is inquiring into
reports that insider rings of solicitors and estate agents are manipulating
the market in repossessed homes.
Mr Edward Leigh, junior trade and industry minister, told the Commons
yesterday that Sir Bryan would consider taking action against individuals
under the 1979 Estate Agents Act.
Under the act the director-general may, in certain circumstances, prohibit
individuals from engaging further in estate agency work.
</TEXT>
